# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anti-environmentalism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was based in Syria from 1979 to 1998.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He helped found the PKK in 1978, and led it into the Kurdish–Turkish conflict in 1984.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] For most of his leadership, he was based in Syria, which provided sanctuary to the PKK until the late 1990s.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The sentence was commuted to aggravated life imprisonment when Turkey abolished the death penalty.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] From 1999 until 2009, he was the sole prisoner in İmralı prison in the Sea of Marmara, where he is still held.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan has advocated for a political solution to the conflict since the 1993 Kurdistan Workers' Party ceasefire. Öcalan's prison regime has oscillated between long periods of isolation during which he is allowed no contact with the outside world, and periods when he is permitted visits.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He was also involved in negotiations with the Turkish government that led to a temporary Kurdish–Turkish peace process in 2013.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In February 2025, he issued a statement from prison calling on the PKK to disarm and disband itself, after which the group's leadership declared a unilateral ceasefire.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] From prison, Öcalan has published several books.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] While some sources report his date of birth as 4 April 1949, no official birth records exist.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He has claimed not to know exactly when he was born, estimating the year to be 1946 or 1947.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He is the oldest of seven children. Öcalan's father was poor even by local standards, and he once said that there was "always fighting" and "an overwhelming unhappiness" in his family.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] When asked about their ethnic origin, his younger brother Osman Öcalan stated that their paternal family was fully Kurdish, while their maternal family was of mixed Kurdish, Turkish, Arab, and Assyrian origins.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] While Abdullah Öcalan claimed that their mother was fully Turkmen, Osman Öcalan disputed it, stating that many Albanian and other Balkan migrants were imported to the region by the Ottomans and identified as Turks, although he did not fully dismiss the possibility of their mother being Turkish.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] After the death of Abdi Ağa, Hüseyin Ağa led more revenge attacks on the Ottomans and drove them away.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The family was celebrated by other Kurds and known as "Mala Ocê" ("House of Revenge").
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] After the Surname Law, the surname was Turkified to "Öcalan", meaning "revengeful".
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Abdullah Öcalan spoke only Kurdish until elementary school, which he attended in a neighboring village.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] After he began school, he learned Turkish and began assimilating.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He was impacted by Turkish nationalist school curriculum and dreamed of joining the Turkish army when he grew up.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He applied to a military high school for future commissioned officers, but had failed the admission exam.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Rejected from the military high school, Öcalan enrolled in a vocational high school in Ankara (Turkish: *Ankara Tapu-Kadastro Meslek Lisesi*) in 1966.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] After graduating in 1969, Öcalan began working at the Title Deeds Office of Diyarbakır.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] It was at this time his political affiliation began to reform.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He was relocated one year later to Istanbul where he participated in the meetings of the Revolutionary Cultural Eastern Hearths (DDKO), a Kurdish organization.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Later, he entered the Istanbul Law Faculty but after the first year transferred to Ankara University to study political science.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] According to a book by journalist Necdet Pekmezci, Öcalan's return to Ankara was facilitated by the state in order to divide the *Dev-Genç* (Revolutionary Youth Federation of Turkey), of which Öcalan was a member.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] President Süleyman Demirel later regretted this decision, since the PKK was to become a much greater threat to the state than *Dev-Genç*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was not able to graduate from Ankara University, as on 7 April 1972 he was arrested after participating in a rally against the killing of Mahir Çayan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He was charged with distributing the left-wing political magazine *Şafak* (published by Doğu Perinçek) and was held for seven months at the Mamak Prison.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In November 1973, the Ankara Democratic Association of Higher Education, (*Ankara Demokratik Yüksek Öğrenim Demeği,* ADYÖD) was founded and shortly after he was elected to join its board.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In the ADYÖD several students close to the political views of Hikmet Kıvılcımlı were active.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In December 1974, *ADYÖD* was closed down.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 1975, together with Mazlum Doğan and Mehmet Hayri Durmuş, he published a political booklet which described the main aims for a *Revolution in Kurdistan*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] During meetings in Ankara between 1974 and 1975, Öcalan and others came to the conclusion that Kurdistan was a colony and preparations ought to be made for a revolution.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The group decided to disperse into the different towns in Turkish Kurdistan in order to set up a base of supporters for an armed revolution.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] At the beginning, this idea had only a few supporters, but following a journey Öcalan made through the cities of Ağrı, Batman, Diyarbakır, Bingöl, Kars and Urfa in 1977, the group counted over 300 adherents and had organised about thirty armed militants.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 1978, in the midst of the right- and left-wing conflicts which culminated in the 1980 Turkish coup d'état, Öcalan founded the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK).
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Since its foundation, the party focused on ideological training.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] "If you break the link between yourself and ideology you will beastialize," he told his followers.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] With the support of the Syrian Government, he established two training camps for the PKK in Lebanon where the Kurdish guerrillas should receive political and military training.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 1984, the PKK initiated a campaign of armed conflict by attacking government forces in order to create an independent Kurdish state. Öcalan attempted to unite the Kurdish liberation movements of the PKK and the one active against Saddam Hussein in Iraq.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In negotiations between the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and the PKK, it was agreed that the latter was able to move freely in Iraqi Kurdistan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He also met twice with Masoud Barzani, the leader of the KDP in Damascus, to resolve some minor issues they had once in 1984 and another time in 1985.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] But due to pressure from Turkey the cooperation remained timid.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] During an interview he gave to the Turkish Milliyet in 1988, he mentioned the goal wasn't to gain independence from Turkey at all costs, but remained firm on the issue of the Kurdish rights, and suggested that negotiations should take place for a federation to be established in Turkey.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 1988, he also met with Jalal Talabani of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) in Damascus, with which he signed an agreement and after some differences after the foundation of a Kurdish Government in Iraqi Kurdistan in 1992 he later had a better relationship.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In the early 1990s, interviews given to both Doğu Perinçek and Hasan Bildirici he mentioned his willingness to achieve a peaceful solution to the conflict.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In another given to Oral Çalışlar, he emphasized the difference between independence and separatism.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He articulated the view that different nations were able to live in independence within the same state if they had equal rights.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Then in 1993, upon request of Turkish president Turgut Özal, Öcalan met with Jalal Talabani for negotiations following which Öcalan declared a unilateral cease fire which had a duration from 20 March to 15 April.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Later he prolonged it in order to enable negotiations with the Turkish government.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Soon after Özal died on 17 April 1993, the initiative was halted by Turkey on the grounds that Turkey did not negotiate with terrorists.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] During an International Kurdish Conference in Brussels in March 1994, his initiative for equal rights for Kurds and Turks within Turkey was discussed.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] It is reported by Gottfried Stein, that at least during the first half of the 1990s, he used to live mainly in a protected neighborhood in Damascus.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] On 7 May 1996, in the midst of another unilateral cease-fire declared by the PKK, an attempt to assassinate him in a house in Damascus, was unsuccessful.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Following the protests which arose against the prohibition of the PKK in Germany, Öcalan had several meetings with politicians from Germany who came to hold talks with him.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Back in Germany, Lummer made a statement in support for further negotiations with Öcalan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] With time, the United States (1997), European Union, Syria, Turkey, and other countries have included the PKK on their lists of terrorist organizations.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] A Greek parliamentary delegation from the PASOK came to visit him in the Beqaa valley on 17 October 1996.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] During his stay in Syria he has published several books concerning the Kurdish revolution.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] On at least one occasion, in 1993, he was detained and held by Syria's General Intelligence Directorate, but later released.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] As the situation deteriorated in Turkey, the Turkish government openly threatened Syria over its support for the PKK.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] As a result, the Syrian government forced Öcalan to leave the country but still refused turning him over to the Turkish authorities.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In October 1998, Öcalan prepared for his departure from Syria and during a meeting in Kobane, he unsuccessfully attempted to lay the foundations for a new party which failed due to Syrian intelligence's obstruction.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan left Syria on 9 October 1998 and for the next four months, he toured several European countries advocating for a solution of the Kurdish-Turkish conflict. Öcalan first went to Russia where the Russian parliament voted on 4 November 1998 to grant him asylum.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] On 6 November 109 Greek parliamentarians invited Öcalan to stay in Greece, a move which was repeated by Panayioitis Sgouridis, the deputy speaker of the Greek Parliament at the time. Öcalan then chose to travel to Italy, where he landed on 12 November 1998 at the airport in Rome.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 1998 the Turkish government requested the extradition of Öcalan from Italy, where he applied for political asylum upon his arrival.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He was detained by the Italian authorities due to an arrest warrant issued by Germany.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] But Italy did not extradite him to Germany, who refused to hold a trial on Öcalan in its country.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The German chancellor Gerhard Schröder as well as the Minister of the Interior Otto Schily preferred that Öcalan would be tried by an unspecified "European Court".
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Italy also didn't extradite him to Turkey.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The Italian prime minister Massimo D'Alema announced it was contrary to Italian law to extradite someone to a country where the defendant is threatened with a capital punishment.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] But Italy also didn't want Öcalan to stay, and pulled several diplomatic strings to compel him to leave the country, which was accomplished on 16 January when he departed to Nizhny Novgorod in hope to find a safe haven in Russia.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] But in Russia he was not as much welcomed as in October, and he had to wait for a week at the airport of Strigino International Airport in Nizhny Novgorod.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] From Russia, he took an airplane from Saint Petersburg to Greece where he arrived in Athens upon the invitation of Nikolas Naxakis, a retired Admiral on 29 January 1999.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He spent the night as a guest of the popular Greek author Voula Damianakou in Nea Makri.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] At that time he was defended by Britta Böhler, a high-profile German attorney who argued that the crimes he was accused of would have to be proven in court and attempted to reach that the International Court in The Hague would assume the case.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was abducted in Kenya on 15 February 1999, while on his way from the Greek embassy to Jomo Kenyatta International Airport in Nairobi, in an operation by the Turkish National Intelligence Organization (Turkish: *Millî İstihbarat Teşkilatı**,* MIT), with the help of the CIA.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Following his capture, the Greek Government was in turmoil and Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos, Interior Minister Alekos Papadopoulos and the Minister of Public Order Philipos Petsalnikos resigned from their posts.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Costoulas, the Greek ambassador who protected him, said that his own life was in danger after the operation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Kurds living in Germany were threatened with deportation if they continued to hold demonstrations in support of Öcalan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The warning came after three Kurds were killed and 16 injured during the 1999 attack on the Israeli consulate in Berlin.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] A group named the *Revenge Hawks of Apo* set fire to a department store in Kadıköy Istanbul, causing the death of 13 people.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In several European capitals and larger cities as well as in Iraq, Iran and also Turkey protests were organized against his capture.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He was brought to İmralı island, where he was interrogated for a period of 10 days without being allowed to see or speak to his lawyers.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] A state security court consisting of one military and two civilian judges was established on İmralı island to try Öcalan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] A delegation of three Dutch lawyers who intended to defend him were not allowed to meet with their client and detained for questioning at the airport on the grounds that they acted as "PKK militants" and not lawyers; they were sent back to the Netherlands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] On the seventh day a judge took part in the interrogations, and prepared a transcript of it.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The trial began on 31 May 1999 on the İmralı island in the Sea of Marmara, and was organized by the Ankara State Security Court.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] During the trial, he was represented by the Asrın Law Office.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] His lawyers had difficulty in representing him adequately as they were allowed only two interviews per week of initially a duration of 20 minutes, and later 1 hour, of which several were cancelled due to "bad weather" or because the authorities didn't give the permission needed for them.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Also his lawyers were unaware of what the charges might be, and received the formal indictment only after excerpts of it were already presented to the press.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The trial was accompanied by arrests of scores of Kurdish politicians from the People's Democracy Party (HADEP).
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In mid-June 1999, the Grand National Assembly of Turkey approved the removal of military judges from the State Security Courts, in an attempt to address criticism from the European Court of Human Rights and a civilian judge assumed the post of the military judge.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Shortly before the verdict was read out by Judge Turgut Okyay, when asked about his final remarks, he again offered to play a role in the peace finding process. Öcalan was charged with treason and separatism and sentenced to death on 29 June 1999.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He was also banned from holding public office for life.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] On the same day, Amnesty International (AI) demanded a re-trial and Human Rights Watch (HRW) questioned the fact that witnesses brought by the defense were not heard in the trial.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 1999 the Turkish Parliament discussed a so-called Repentance Bill which would commute Öcalans death sentence to 20 years imprisonment and allow PKK militants to surrender with a limited amnesty, but it didn't pass due to resistance from the far-right around the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP).
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In January 2000 the Turkish government declared the death sentence was delayed until the European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) reviewed the verdict.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Upon the abolition of the death penalty in Turkey in August 2002, in October of that year, the security court commuted his sentence to life imprisonment.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In an attempt to reach a verdict which was more favorable to Öcalan, he appealed at the ECHR at Strasbourg, which accepted the case in June 2004.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 2005, the ECHR ruled that Turkey had violated articles 3, 5, and 6 of the European Convention of Human Rights by refusing to allow Öcalan to appeal his arrest and by sentencing him to death without a fair trial. Öcalan's request for a retrial was refused by Turkish courts.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] After his capture, Öcalan was held in solitary confinement as the only prisoner on İmralı island in the Sea of Marmara.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Following the commutation of the death sentence to a life sentence in 2002, Öcalan remained imprisoned on İmralı, and was the sole inmate there.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Although former prisoners at İmralı were transferred to other prisons, more than 1,000 Turkish military personnel were stationed on the island to guard him.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In November 2009, Turkish authorities announced that they were ending his solitary confinement by transferring several other prisoners to İmralı.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] They said that Öcalan would be allowed to see them for ten hours a week.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The new prison was built after the Council of Europe's Committee for the Prevention of Torture visited the island and objected to the conditions in which he was being held.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] From 27 July 2011 until 2 May 2019 his lawyers have not been allowed to see Abdullah Öcalan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] From July 2011 until December 2017 his lawyers filed more than 700 appeals for visits, but all were rejected.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] There have been held regular demonstrations by the Kurdish community to raise awareness of the isolation of Öcalan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In October 2012 several hundred Kurdish political prisoners went on hunger strike for better detention conditions for Öcalan and the right to use the Kurdish language in education and jurisprudence.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The hunger strike lasted 68 days until Öcalan demanded its end. Öcalan was banned from receiving visits almost two years from 6 October 2014 until 11 September 2016, when his brother Mehmet Öcalan visited him for Eid al-Adha.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 2014 the ECHR ruled in that there was a violation of article 3 in regards of him being to only prisoner on İmarli island until 17 November 2009, as well as the impossibility to appeal his verdict.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] On 6 September 2018 visits from lawyers were banned for six months due to former punishments he received in the years 2005–2009, the fact that the lawyers made their conversations with Ocalan public, and the impression that Öcalan was leading the PKK through communications with his lawyers.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He was again banned from receiving visits until 12 January 2019 when his brother was permitted to visit him a second time.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The ban on the visitation of his lawyers was lifted in April 2019, and Öcalan saw his lawyers on 2 May 2019.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In January 1999 during his stay in Europe, Öcalan saw the parties liberation struggle focus to have developed from guerrilla warfare to dialogue and negotiations.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] After his capture Öcalan called for a halt in PKK attacks, and advocated for a peaceful solution for the Kurdish conflict inside the borders of Turkey.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In October 1999, eight PKK militants around the former European PKK spokesman Ali Sapan turned themselves in to Turkey on request of Öcalan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Depending on their treatment, the other PKK militants would turn themselves in as well, his attorney announced.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] A similar structure began functioning in May 2006.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] With this process, the way to democratic dialogue will be also opened".
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Though the Turkish government had received Öcalan's protocols, they were never released to the public. Öcalan said he would leave the top PKK commanders in charge of the conflict, but that this should not be misinterpreted as a call for the PKK to intensify its armed conflict with Turkey.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In January 2013, peace negotiations between the PKK and the Turkish Government were initiated and from between January and March he met several times with politicians of Peace and Democracy Party (BDP) on Imralı Island.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] On 21 March, Öcalan declared a ceasefire between the PKK and the Turkish state. Öcalan's statement was read to hundreds of thousands of Kurds in Diyarbakır who had gathered to celebrate the Kurdish New Year (*Newroz*).
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The statement said in part, "Let guns be silenced and politics dominate... a new door is being opened from the process of armed conflict to democratization and democratic politics.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] It's the start of a new era." Soon after Öcalan's declaration, the functional head of the PKK, Murat Karayılan responded by promising to implement a ceasefire.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] During the peace process, the pro-Kurdish Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) entered parliament during the parliamentarian election of June 2015.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The ceasefire ended following the 2014 Kobanî protests and after two Turkish police officers were killed in Ceylanpınar in July 2015, leading to the 2015–2016 Kurdish–Turkish conflict.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] On 27 February 2025, Öcalan issued a message from prison calling for the PKK to hold a congress dissolving itself and lay down its weapons, kicking off the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In response, the PKK announced that it had begun a ceasefire on 1 March.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Following the PKK's decision to dissolve itself in May 2025, Öcalan issued a message the following month announcing the end of the PKK insurgency against the Turkish state.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Since his incarceration, Öcalan has significantly changed his ideology through exposure to Western social theorists such as Murray Bookchin, Immanuel Wallerstein and Hannah Arendt.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Abandoning his old Marxism–Leninist and Stalinist beliefs, Öcalan fashioned his ideal society called democratic confederalism.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In early 2004, Öcalan attempted to arrange a meeting with Murray Bookchin through Öcalan's lawyers, describing himself as Bookchin's "student" eager to adapt Bookchin's thought to Middle Eastern society.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Bookchin was too ill to meet with Öcalan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In this zone, three bodies of law would be implemented: EU law, Turkish/Syrian/Iraqi/Iranian law and Kurdish law.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] While some of his followers questioned Öcalan's conversion from Marxism-Leninism to social ecology, the PKK adopted Öcalan's proposal and began to form assemblies.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] All are welcome to partake in the communal councils, but political participation is not mandated.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] There is no private property, but rather "ownership by use, which grants individuals usage rights to the buildings, land, and infrastructure, but not the right to sell and buy on the market or convert them to private enterprises".
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The economy is in the hands of the communal councils, and is thus (in the words of Bookchin) 'neither collectivised nor privatised - it is common.' Feminism, ecology, and direct democracy are essential in democratic confederalism.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Parallel to Democratic Confederalism, Öcalan introduced the principle of the Brotherhood of Peoples in 2013, aimed at promoting peaceful coexistence between Kurds and other ethnic groups, similar to the Marxist concept of the friendship of peoples.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] During the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process, Öcalan repeatedly emphasized the Brotherhood of Peoples, stating that it had "reached a threshold" and referring to a "1000-year-old" historical brotherhood between Kurds and Turks.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan is a supporter of the liberation of the women, he writes in his Freedom Manifesto for Women that all slavery is based on the housewifization of women.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He deems the woman often as being trapped in a situation where she accepts traditional gender roles and a disadvantaged relationship with a man.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In the context of Turkey and the activities of the HDP, and now DEM Party, this approach has been described by as Turkeyification, which critics characterize as a form of voluntary Turkification.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] The Middle East Forum described Öcalan's stance in the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process as paradoxical, noting that the PKK was originally founded in response to the denial of Kurdish existence in Turkey.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan's Brotherhood of Peoples concept has also faced similar criticism.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Some commentators have described it as a "project that was born rejected," particularly after Arab tribes defected from the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) during the 2026 northeastern Syria offensive, which may have contributed to the collapse of the DAANES.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] During Öcalan's childhood, his mother, Esma Öcalan (Uveys) was rather dominant and criticised his father, blaming him for their dire economic situation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He later explained in an interview that it was in his childhood he learned to defend himself from injustice.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Like many Kurds in Turkey, Öcalan was raised speaking Turkish; according to Amikam Nachmani, lecturer at the Bar-Ilan University in Israel, Öcalan did not know Kurdish when he met him in 1991.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Nachmani: "*He [Öcalan] told me that he speaks Turkish, gives orders in Turkish, and thinks in Turkish."* In 1978 Öcalan married Kesire Yildirim, who he had met at the Ankara University and was of a better household than the regular revolutionaries around Öcalan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] They had a difficult marriage with reportedly many disputes and discussions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] In 1988, while representing the PKK in Athens, Greece, his wife unsuccessfully attempted to overthrow Öcalan, following which Yildirim went underground.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] After his sister Havva was married to a man from another village in an arranged marriage, he felt regret.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] This event led Öcalan to his policies towards the liberation of women from the traditional suppressed female role. Öcalan's brother Osman became a PKK commander until he defected from the PKK with several others to establish the Patriotic and Democratic Party of Kurdistan.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] His other brother, Mehmet Öcalan, is a member of the pro-Kurdish Peace and Democracy Party (BDP).
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Fatma Öcalan is the sister of Abdullah Öcalan and Dilek Öcalan, a former parliamentarian of the HDP, is his niece. Ömer Öcalan, a current member of parliament for the HDP, is his nephew.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan is the author of more than 40 books, four of which were written in prison.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] Many of the notes taken from his weekly meetings with his lawyers have been edited and published.
[src:anti-environmentalism/abdullah-öcalan] He has also written articles for the newspaper Özgür Gündem which is a newspaper that reported on the Kurdish-Turkish conflict, under the pseudonym of Ali Firat.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt won his seat in the 2010 federal election, becoming the first member of the Greens elected to the House of Representatives at a federal election, and the second overall after Michael Organ, who was elected at a by-election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt first contested the seat in 2007, narrowly losing to the Labor Party's Lindsay Tanner.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Following his success in the 2010 election, Bandt retained the seat in the 2013, 2016, 2019, and 2022 elections.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] He was elected leader of the Greens following the resignation of Richard Di Natale in February 2020.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt lost his seat of Melbourne to Labor's Sarah Witty at the 2025 Australian federal election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] He became the chief executive officer of the Australian Conservation Foundation in January 2026.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Adam Paul Bandt was born in Adelaide on 11 March 1972.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] His mother, a teacher and school principal, was born in England and arrived in Australia as a Ten Pound Pom.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] His father was a social worker who later ran a human resources consultancy.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] He is of Barossa German descent on his father's side.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt moved to Perth at about the age of 10 and attended Hollywood Senior High School.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] While in high school, Bandt went to his first demonstration, protesting against a visit of a nuclear-powered ship to Fremantle.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In his mid-teens, from 1987 to 1989, he was a member of the Australian Labor Party (ALP).
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt later stated he had left the party because of the removal of free university under Hawke and Keating, and blamed the Higher Education Contributions Scheme.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt stated the change "started making education so expensive and putting people in debt".
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] At Murdoch University, Bandt was a student activist and member of the Left Alliance.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] During university, he stated he was inspired by the thought of Leon Trotsky.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] He was president of the student union and an active campaigner for higher living allowances for students, and for free education.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] After finishing university, Bandt worked for student unions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] During the period before his election to parliament in 2010, he lived in Parkville, Victoria and worked as an industrial and public interest lawyer, becoming a partner at Slater & Gordon, with unions for clients.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] He had articles published on links between anti-terror legislation and labour laws and worked on issues facing outworkers in the textiles industry.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In 2006, Bandt published a paper entitled "The Wages of Fear: Labour Laws and Terror".
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In 2008, having gone part-time at Slater & Gordon in order to do so, Bandt completed a PhD at Monash University, supervised by cultural theorist Andrew Milner, with his thesis titled "Work to Rule: Rethinking Pashukanis, Marx and Law".
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] His thesis was embargoed for three years in the hopes of having it published as a book.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In 2009, Bandt published a paper arguing that emergencies, such as the 2008 financial crisis and war on terror, have been used by neoliberal "strong states" to "undermine basic rights".
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt was preselected to stand as the Greens candidate for the federal division of Melbourne at the 2007 election against Labor's Lindsay Tanner, the incumbent Shadow Minister for Finance, who retained the seat.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt finished with 22.8 percent of the primary vote, an increase of 3.8 percent, and 45.3 percent of the two-candidate preferred vote after out-polling the Liberal Party's Andrea Del Ciotto following the allocation of preferences.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Nationally, he was the most successful candidate of any minor party contesting a House of Representatives seat.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Following the 2007 federal election Melbourne had become Australia's only Labor/Greens marginal seat.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt was preselected as Greens candidate for the second time, and ran successfully against a new Labor candidate, Cath Bowtell, at the 2010 federal election following Lindsay Tanner's retirement.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt received a primary vote of 36.2 percent and a two-party-preferred vote of 56 percent against Labor, a swing to him of 13.4 and 10.8 points, respectively.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] He was elected on the ninth count after over three-quarters of Liberal preferences flowed to him, enabling him to overtake Bowtell and become the first Green candidate to win a seat in a general election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In 2012, Bandt was elected deputy leader of the Greens following Bob Brown's retirement from politics and as leader of the Greens.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In the 2013 federal election, Bandt was re-elected to the seat of Melbourne, despite an overall decrease in the Greens' vote and Liberal Party directing preferences to Labor ahead of The Greens.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt retained the seat with a 42.6% primary and 55.2% two-party-preferred vote, with his two-candidate majority almost untouched.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt sat on Christine Milne's frontbench.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In 2015, upon the change of Green leadership from Christine Milne to Richard Di Natale, Bandt did not re-contest the deputy leadership saying he had a baby due in the upcoming weeks.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Scott Ludlam and Larissa Waters were elected unopposed as co-deputies.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt was re-elected as Member for Melbourne for a third time at the 2016 election, pushing Labor into third place, and the overwhelming preference for him over the Liberals from Labor voters allowed him to increase his two-candidate-preferred vote to 68.48%.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In 2017, the Party's co-deputy leaders Larissa Waters and Scott Ludlam were found to be ineligible to sit in Australia's Parliament owing to their status as dual citizens.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Rachel Siewert and Bandt were made temporary co-deputy leaders.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt achieved national headlines in February 2018 for accusing new senator Jim Molan of war crimes after it was revealed that Molan had shared anti-Muslim content made by far-right party Britain First on their Facebook account.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt retained his seat of Melbourne at the 2019 federal election with a primary vote of 49.3%, the highest primary vote for the Greens in the history of the electorate.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt also received a 4.8% swing in his favour at the election, and his two-party preferred vote against the Liberals rose to 71.8%.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] The Greens' primary vote in Melbourne (49.3%) was larger than the combined Liberal and Labor vote, of 21.5% and 19.7% respectively, and almost twice as high as their second-highest primary vote (in Wills).
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] On 3 February 2020, Richard Di Natale announced his resignation as leader of the Greens and imminent retirement from politics, citing family reasons.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt announced his candidacy for the leadership shortly after.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] On 4 February, he was elected unopposed.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Larissa Waters was elected unopposed as co-deputy, with Nick McKim defeating Sarah Hanson-Young and Mehreen Faruqi to become the second co-deputy.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt has been described by the political journalist Paddy Manning as the first Greens leader from the Left wing of the party.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] He has adopted a pro-mining message, but with a focus on expanding the lithium industry and other minerals necessary for a zero-carbon economy; rather than using coal.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Under Bandt's vision, the party aspired to develop a power-sharing situation with a Labor government at the 2022 election, similar to the Gillard era.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Whilst serving as party leader, Bandt also acted as the Greens' spokesperson for: the Climate Emergency, Energy, Employment & Workplace Relations, and the Public Sector.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In the 2022 federal election, Bandt retained his seat in Melbourne with a primary vote of 49.6%, beating that of his previous election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] However, there was a 12.4% swing against him in the two-candidate-preferred vote.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] The Greens gained three further seats in the House of Representatives and three in the Senate, with an increase in the first-preference vote by 1.9% to 12.3%.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] On 19 June 2022, Bandt had the Australian flag removed from behind the podium at a media conference of his, saying that it "represented lingering pain" for some Australians.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] On 9 September 2022, one day after the death of Queen Elizabeth II, Bandt tweeted "Rest In Peace Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Our thoughts are with her family and all who loved her.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt led the Greens into the 2025 election and saw the Greens lose all but one of their seats in the House of Representatives.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt himself lost his seat in the division of Melbourne following a 5.27% decrease in his primary vote and a 8.60% swing against him on a two candidate preferred basis to the Labor Party's candidate Sarah Witty.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Following the poor results for the Greens, Bandt resigned as leader of the party.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] He considered running for the seat again but felt "you have to be more than fully committed to do that, and I've climbed that mountain.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Band briefly returned to work as an employment lawyer with the United Firefighters Union (UFU) before contacting the Australian Conservation Foundation (ACF), who were seeking a new chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] In September 2025, the ACF announced that Bandt would become the next CEO of their organisation from January 2026.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] They also confirmed that he would not play "any further active role in the Greens".
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt sought to strengthen the ACF through membership building, creating a "people power movement as big as the one that stopped the Franklin dam".
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt was widely viewed as on the left of the Australian Greens.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt was described as different to previous Greens leaders due to his emphasis on "public ownership, public wealth, and community-driven responses to the links between climate change and capitalism".
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Following Virgin Australia undergoing voluntary administration in 2020, Bandt called for the government to purchase the airline "at bargain basement prices".
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] These economic views form the crux of Bandt's opposition to neoliberalism, with Bandt viewing the rise of right-wing populism since the Great Recession as part of a backlash to neoliberal economics.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt believes that Australia should become a republic.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt is a strong supporter of many progressive reforms, including the Indigenous Voice to Parliament, a federal treaty with Indigenous Australians, banning fossil fuels, and legalising recreational cannabis usage.
[src:anti-environmentalism/adam-bandt] Bandt married former Labor staffer Claudia Perkins in 2013.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The son of politician Albert Gore Sr., Gore was raised in Tennessee and Washington, D.C., where he was born.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] After graduating from Harvard University and serving in the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Army, he quit law school to run as a representative for Tennessee's 4th congressional district in 1976.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was re-elected three times before running for U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Senate in 1984, winning re-election in 1990.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was considered a moderate and an "Atari Democrat".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore served as vice president during the Clinton administration from 1993 to 2001, defeating then-incumbents George H.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Bush and Dan Quayle in 1992, and Bob Dole and Jack Kemp in 1996, and was the first Democrat to serve two full terms as vice president since John Nance Garner.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] As of 2025, Gore's 1990 re-election remains the last time Democrats won a Senate election in Tennessee.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was the Democratic presidential nominee in the 2000 election, in which he lost the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Electoral College vote by five electoral votes to Republican nominee George W.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Bush while winning the popular vote by 543,895 votes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore* against a previous ruling by the Supreme Court of Florida on a re-count.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He is one of five presidential candidates in American history to lose a presidential election despite winning the popular vote.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] After his vice presidency ended in 2001, Gore remained prominent as an author and environmental activist, and his work in climate change activism earned him (jointly with the IPCC) the Nobel Peace Prize in 2007.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore is the founder and chair of The Climate Reality Project, the co-founder and chair of Generation Investment Management, the since-defunct Current TV network, a former member of the Board of Directors of Apple Inc. and a senior adviser to Google.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore is also a partner in the venture capital firm Kleiner Perkins, heading its climate change solutions group.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He has served as a visiting professor at Middle Tennessee State University, Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism, Fisk University, and the University of California, Los Angeles.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He served on the Board of Directors of World Resources Institute.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore has received a number of awards that include the Nobel Peace Prize (joint award with the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, 2007), a Primetime Emmy Award for Current TV (2007), and a Webby Award (2005).
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was also the subject of the Academy Award winning (2007) documentary *An Inconvenient Truth* in 2006, as well as its 2017 sequel *An Inconvenient Sequel: Truth to Power*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 2007, he was named a runner-up for *Time*'s 2007 Person of the Year.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 2008, Gore won the Dan David Prize for Social Responsibility, and in 2024 was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Joe Biden.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Albert Arnold Gore Jr. was born on March 31, 1948, in Washington, D.C., as the second of two children born to Albert Gore Sr., a U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Representative who later served for 18 years as a U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Senator from Tennessee, and Pauline LaFon Gore, one of the first women to graduate from the Vanderbilt University Law School.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore is a descendant of Scots Irish immigrants who first settled in Virginia during the mid-17th-century and moved to Tennessee after the Revolutionary War.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His older sister Nancy LaFon Gore died of lung cancer in 1984.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During the school year he lived with his family in The Fairfax Hotel in the Embassy Row section in Washington D.C.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During the summer months, he worked on the family farm in Carthage, Tennessee, where the Gores grew tobacco and hay and raised cattle.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Albans School, an independent college preparatory day and boarding school for boys in Washington, D.C., from 1956 to 1965, a prestigious feeder school for the Ivy League.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was the captain of the football team, threw discus for the track and field team and participated in basketball, art, and government.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He graduated 25th in a class of 51, applied to one college, Harvard University, and was accepted.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore enrolled in Harvard College in 1965; he initially planned to major in English and write novels but later decided to major in government.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On his second day on campus, he began campaigning for the freshman student government council and was elected its president.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was roommates with future actor Tommy Lee Jones in Dunster House.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was an avid reader who fell in love with scientific and mathematical theories, but he did not do well in science classes and avoided taking math.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During his first two years, his grades placed him in the lower one-fifth of his class.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During his second year, he reportedly spent much of his time watching television, shooting pool and occasionally smoking marijuana.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In his junior and senior years, he became more involved with his studies, earning As and Bs.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In his senior year, he took a class with oceanographer and global warming theorist Roger Revelle, who sparked Gore's interest in global warming and other environmental issues.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore earned an A on his thesis, "The Impact of Television on the Conduct of the Presidency, 1947–1969", and graduated with an A.B.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was in college during the era of anti-Vietnam War protests.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was opposed to the war but disagreed with the tactics of the student protest movement, and believed it to be juvenile and misguided to use a private university as a venue to vent anger at the war.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He and his friends did not participate in Harvard demonstrations.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] John Tyson, a former roommate, recalled, "We distrusted these movements a lot ...
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore and his sister, Nancy, accompanied their parents to the 1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] With his father being a senator, his family had tickets to sit inside of the convention hall at the International Amphitheatre.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He helped write an anti-war address that his father delivered to the convention.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] While at the convention, Gore witnessed some of the protests in the streets, but remained with his parents inside of their hotel room when violence erupted at the protests.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] When Gore graduated in 1969, he immediately became eligible for the military draft.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His father, a vocal anti-Vietnam War critic, was facing re-election in 1970.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore eventually decided that enlisting in the Army would be the best course between serving his country, his personal values and interests.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Although nearly all of his Harvard classmates avoided the draft and service in Vietnam, Gore believed if he found a way around military service, he would be handing an issue to his father's Republican opponent.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] According to Gore's Senate biography, "He appeared in uniform in his father's campaign commercials, one of which ended with his father advising: 'Son, always love your country'." Despite this, Gore Sr. lost the election to an opponent who vastly out-fundraised him.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] This opponent was later found by the Watergate commission to have accepted illegal money from Nixon's operatives.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore has said that his other reason for enlisting was that he did not want someone with fewer options than he to go in his place.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Actor Tommy Lee Jones, a former college housemate, recalled Gore saying that "if he found a fancy way of not going, someone else would have to go in his place".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] After enlisting in August 1969, Gore returned to the anti war Harvard campus in his military uniform to say goodbye to his adviser and was "jeered" at by students.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He later said he was astonished by the "emotional field of negativity and disapproval and piercing glances that ... certainly felt like real hatred".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore had basic training at Fort Dix from August to October, and then was assigned to be a journalist at Fort Rucker, Alabama.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In April 1970, he was named Rucker's "Soldier of the Month".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His orders to be sent to Vietnam were "held up" for some time and the Gore family suspected that this was due to a fear by the Nixon administration that if something happened to him, his father would gain sympathy votes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was finally shipped to Vietnam on January 2, 1971, after his father had lost his seat in the Senate during the 1970 Senate election, becoming one "of only about a dozen of the 1,115 Harvard graduates in the [all-male] Class of '69 who went to Vietnam".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was stationed with the 20th Engineer Brigade in Biên Hòa and was a journalist with *The Castle Courier.* He received an honorable discharge from the Army in May 1971.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Of his time in the Army, Gore later stated, "I didn't do the most, or run the gravest danger.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was "dispirited" after his return from Vietnam.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The *Nashville Scene* later noted that "his father's defeat made service in a conflict he deeply opposed even more abhorrent to Gore.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His experiences in the war zone don't seem to have been deeply traumatic in themselves; although the engineers were sometimes fired upon, Gore has said he didn't see full-scale combat.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Still, he felt that his participation in the war was wrong." Although his parents wanted him to go to law school, Gore first attended Vanderbilt University Divinity School (1971–1972) on a Rockefeller Foundation scholarship for people planning secular careers.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He later said he went there in order to explore "spiritual issues", and that "he had hoped to make sense of the social injustices that seemed to challenge his religious beliefs".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1971, Gore began to work the night shift for *The Tennessean* as an investigative reporter.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His investigations of corruption among members of Nashville's Metro Council resulted in the arrest and prosecution of two councilmen for separate offenses.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1974, he took a leave of absence from *The Tennessean* to attend Vanderbilt University Law School.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His decision to become an attorney was a partial result of his time as a journalist, as he realized that, while he could expose corruption, he could not change it.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore did not complete law school, deciding abruptly in 1976 to run for a seat in the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] House of Representatives when he found out that his father's former seat in the House was about to be vacated.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Congress at the age of 28 and stayed there for the next 16 years, serving in both the House (1977–1985) and the Senate (1985–1993).
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore spent many weekends in Tennessee, working with his constituents.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Evins unexpectedly announced his retirement from Congress, making Tennessee's 4th congressional district seat, to which he had succeeded Albert Gore Sr. in 1953, open.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore won the 1976 Democratic primary for the district with "32 percent of the vote, three percentage points more than his nearest rival", and was opposed by only an independent candidate in the election, recording 94 percent of the overall vote.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He went on to win the next three elections, in 1978, 1980 and 1982, where "he was unopposed twice and won 79 percent of the vote the other time".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1984, Gore successfully ran for a seat in the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Senate, which had been vacated by Republican Senate Majority Leader Howard Baker.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was "unopposed in the Democratic Senatorial primary and won the general election going away", despite the fact that Republican President Ronald Reagan swept Tennessee in his reelection campaign the same year.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore defeated Republican senatorial nominee Victor Ashe, subsequently the mayor of Knoxville, and the Republican-turned-Independent, Ed McAteer, founder of the Christian right Religious Roundtable organization that had worked to elect Reagan as president in 1980.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During his time in Congress, Gore was considered a moderate, once referring to himself as a "raging moderate", opposing federal funding of abortion, voting in favor of a bill which supported a moment of silence in schools, and voting against a ban on interstate sales of guns.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During his tenure in the House, Gore voted in favor of the bill establishing Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] While Gore initially did not vote on the Civil Rights Restoration Act of 1987 in January 1988, he voted to override President Reagan's veto the following March.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore voted against the nomination of William Rehnquist as Chief Justice of the United States, as well as the nominations of Robert Bork and Clarence Thomas to the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During his time in the House, Gore sat on the Energy and Commerce and the Science and Technology committees, chairing the Science Committee's Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations for four years.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He also sat on the House Intelligence Committee and, in 1982, introduced the *Gore Plan* for arms control, to "reduce chances of a nuclear first strike by cutting multiple warheads and deploying single-warhead mobile launchers".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] While in the Senate, he sat on the Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs, the Rules and Administration, and the Armed Services Committees.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1991, Gore was one of ten Democrats who supported the Gulf War.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was considered one of the *Atari Democrats*, given this name due to their "passion for technological issues, from biomedical research and genetic engineering to the environmental impact of the "greenhouse effect".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On March 19, 1979, he had become the first member of Congress to appear on C-SPAN.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During this time, Gore co-chaired the Congressional Clearinghouse on the Future with Newt Gingrich.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In addition, he has been described as having been a "genuine nerd, with a geek reputation running back to his days as a futurist *Atari Democrat* in the House.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore introduced the Supercomputer Network Study Act of 1986.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He also sponsored hearings on how advanced technologies might be put to use in areas like coordinating the response of government agencies to natural disasters and other crises.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The bill was passed on December 9, 1991, and led to the National Information Infrastructure (NII) which Gore referred to as the "information superhighway".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] After joining the House of Representatives, Gore held the "first congressional hearings on the climate change, and co-sponsor[ed] hearings on toxic waste and global warming".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He continued to speak on the topic throughout the 1980s.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1990, Senator Gore presided over a three-day conference with legislators from over 42 countries which sought to create a *Global Marshall Plan,* "under which industrial nations would help less developed countries grow economically while still protecting the environment".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On April 3, 1989, Al, Tipper and their six-year-old son Albert were leaving a baseball game.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Albert ran across the street to see his friend and was hit by a car.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was thrown 30 feet (9 m) and then traveled along the pavement for another 20 feet (6 m).
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore later recalled: "I ran to his side and held him and called his name, but he was motionless, limp and still, without breath or pulse....
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His eyes were open with the nothingness stare of death, and we prayed, the two of us, there in the gutter, with only my voice." Albert was tended to by two nurses who happened to be present during the accident.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The Gores spent the next month in the hospital with Albert.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore also commented: "Our lives were consumed with the struggle to restore his body and spirit." This event was "a trauma so shattering that [Gore] views it as a moment of personal rebirth", a "key moment in his life" which "changed everything".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In August 1991, Gore announced that his son's accident was a factor in his decision not to run for president in 1992.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore stated: "I would like to be President....
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] But I am also a father, and I feel deeply about my responsibility to my children....
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] I didn't feel right about tearing myself away from my family to the extent that is necessary in a Presidential campaign." During this time, Gore wrote *Earth in the Balance*, a text that became the first book written by a sitting U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Senator to make *The New York Times* Best Seller list since John F.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1988, Gore sought the Democratic Party's nomination for President of the United States.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore carried seven states in the primaries, finishing third overall in a field that included Massachusetts Governor Michael Dukakis, then Senator Joe Biden (who would later become Vice President and then President), Gary Hart, Congressman Dick Gephardt, Paul Simon and Jesse Jackson.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Dukakis eventually won the Democratic nomination and went on to lose in a landslide to George H.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Although Gore initially denied that he intended to run, his candidacy was the subject of speculation: "National analysts make Sen.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore a long-shot for the Presidential nomination, but many believe he could provide a natural complement for any of the other candidates: a young, attractive, moderate Vice Presidential nominee from the South.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He currently denies any interest, but he carefully does not reject the idea out of hand." At the time, he was 39 years old, making him the "youngest serious Presidential candidate since John F.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] CNN noted that, "in 1988, for the first time, 12 southern states would hold their primaries on the same day, dubbed 'Super Tuesday'.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore thought he would be the only serious Southern contender; he had not counted on Jesse Jackson." Jackson defeated Gore in the South Carolina primary, winning, "more than half the total vote, three times that of his closest rival here, Senator Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore next placed great hope on Super Tuesday where they split the Southern vote: Jackson winning Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi and Virginia; Gore winning Arkansas, North Carolina, Kentucky, Nevada, Tennessee, and Oklahoma.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was later endorsed by New York City Mayor Ed Koch who made statements in favor of Israel and against Jackson.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] These statements cast Gore in a negative light, leading voters away from Gore who received only 10% of the vote in the New York primary.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] *The New York Times* said that Gore also lost support due to his attacks against Jackson, Dukakis, and others.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was eventually able to mend fences with Jackson, who supported the Clinton-Gore ticket in 1992 and 1996, and campaigned for the Gore-Lieberman ticket during the 2000 presidential election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore's policies changed substantially in 2000, reflecting his eight years as vice president.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was initially hesitant to be Bill Clinton's running mate for the 1992 United States presidential election; after clashing with the George H.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Bush administration over global warming issues, he decided to accept the offer.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Clinton stated that he chose Gore due to his foreign policy experience, work with the environment, and commitment to his family.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Clinton's choice was criticized as unconventional because rather than picking a running mate who would diversify the ticket, Clinton chose a fellow Southerner who shared his political ideologies and who was nearly the same age as Clinton.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The Washington Bureau Chief for *The Baltimore Sun*, Paul West, later suggested that "Al Gore revolutionized the way Vice Presidents are made.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] When he joined Bill Clinton's ticket, it violated the old rules.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Not with two Southerners from neighboring states.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] A couple of left-of-center moderates. ...
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Clinton and Gore accepted the nomination at the Democratic National Convention on July 17, 1992.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Known as the *Baby Boomer Ticket* and the *Fortysomething Team,* *The New York Times* noted that if elected, Clinton and Gore, at ages 46 and 44 respectively, would be the "youngest team to make it to the White House in the country's history".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore called the ticket "a new generation of leadership".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The ticket increased in popularity after the candidates traveled with their wives, Hillary and Tipper, on a "six-day, 1,000-mile bus ride, from New York to St.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Al Gore would participate in one vice-presidential debate against Vice President Dan Quayle, and Admiral James Stockdale.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] That debate, as of 2023, was the only televised Vice-Presidential debate with more than two participating candidates.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The Clinton-Gore ticket beat the Bush-Quayle and Perot-Stockdale tickets with 43% of the popular vote, versus their 38% and 19%, respectively.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Clinton and Gore received 370 electoral votes, versus the incumbent ticket's 168, and Perot's 0.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Al Gore served as vice president during the Clinton administration.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Clinton and Gore were inaugurated on January 20, 1993.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] At the beginning of the first term, they developed a "two-page agreement outlining their relationship".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Clinton committed himself to regular lunch meetings; he recognized Gore as a principal adviser on nominations and appointed some of Gore's chief advisers to key White House staff positions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Clinton involved Gore in decision-making to an unprecedented degree for a vice president.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Through their weekly lunches and daily conversations, Gore became the president's "indisputable chief adviser".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore had to compete with First Lady Hillary for President Clinton's influence, starting when she was appointed to the health-care task force without Gore's consultation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] *Vanity Fair* wrote that President Clinton's "failure to confide in his vice president was a telling sign of the real pecking order", and reported "it was an open secret that some of Hillary's advisers...nurtured dreams that Hillary, not Gore, would follow Bill in the presidency".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore had a particular interest in reducing "waste, fraud, and abuse in the federal government and advocated trimming the size of the bureaucracy and the number of regulations".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During the Clinton administration, the U.S. economy expanded; according to David Greenberg (professor of history and media studies at Rutgers University), "by the end of the Clinton presidency, the numbers were uniformly impressive.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Clinton and Gore entered office planning to finance research that would "flood the economy with innovative goods and services, lifting the general level of prosperity and strengthening American industry".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Their overall aim was to fund the development of, "robotics, smart roads, biotechnology, machine tools, magnetic-levitation trains, fiber-optic communications and national computer networks.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Also earmarked [were] a raft of basic technologies like digital imaging and data storage." Critics claimed that the initiatives would "backfire, bloating Congressional pork and creating whole new categories of Federal waste".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During the election and his term as vice president, Gore popularized the term "Information Superhighway", which became synonymous with the Internet, and he was involved in the creation of the National Information Infrastructure.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore first discussed his plans to emphasize information technology at UCLA on January 11, 1994, in a speech at The Superhighway Summit.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On March 29, 1994, Gore made the inaugural keynote to a Georgetown University symposium on governmental reform with a lecture entitled, "The new job of the federal executive".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was involved in a number of projects including NetDay '96 and 24 Hours in Cyberspace.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The Clinton–Gore administration also launched the first official White House website in 1994 and subsequent versions through 2000.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During 1993 and early 1994, Gore was tapped by the administration to advocate for the adoption of the Clipper Chip, a technology developed by the National Security Agency designed to provide for law enforcement access to encrypted communications.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] After political and technical objections, the initiative was essentially dropped.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was also involved in environmental initiatives.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He launched the GLOBE program on Earth Day '94, an education and science activity that, according to *Forbes*, "made extensive use of the Internet to increase student awareness of their environment".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1998, Gore began promoting a NASA satellite (Deep Space Climate Observatory) that would provide a constant view of the Earth, marking the first time such an image would have been made since *The Blue Marble* photo from the 1972 Apollo 17 mission.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During this time, he also became associated with Digital Earth.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] 98), which declared opposition to any greenhouse gas treaty which would limit US emissions without similar limits on third-world countries such as China.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The Clinton administration left office three years later without having submitted the treaty for ratification.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1996, Gore became involved in a "Chinagate" campaign finance controversy over his attendance at an event at the Buddhist Hsi Lai Temple in Hacienda Heights, California.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In an interview on NBC's *Today* the following year, Gore said, "I did not know that it was a fund-raiser.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] I knew it was a political event, and I knew there were finance people that were going to be present, and so that alone should have told me, 'This is inappropriate and this is a mistake; don't do this.' And I take responsibility for that.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Department of Justice investigation into the fund-raising activities had uncovered evidence that Chinese agents sought to direct contributions from foreign sources to the Democratic National Committee (DNC) before the 1996 presidential campaign.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The Chinese embassy in Washington, D.C. was used for coordinating contributions to the DNC.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] FBI agents were denied the opportunity to ask President Bill Clinton and Vice President Al Gore questions during Justice Department interviews in 1997 and 1998 and were allowed only to take notes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In March 1997, Gore had to explain phone calls which he made to solicit funds for Democratic Party for the 1996 election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In a news conference, Gore stated that, "all calls that I made were charged to the Democratic National Committee.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] I was advised there was nothing wrong with that.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In the spring of 2000, Conrad asked Reno to appoint an independent counsel to continue the investigation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] After looking into the matter, Reno judged that the appointment of an independent counsel was unwarranted.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During the 1990s, Gore spoke out on a number of issues.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 1998, at a conference of APEC hosted by Malaysia, Gore objected to the indictment, arrest and jailing of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's longtime second-in-command Anwar Ibrahim, a move which received a negative response from leaders there.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Ten years later, Gore again protested when Ibrahim was arrested a second time, a decision condemned by Malaysian foreign minister Datuk Seri Dr Rais Yatim.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In the 1996 presidential election, Clinton and Gore both ran for re-election for president and vice-president.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] They faced Republican Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, with his running mate, Jack Kemp, a former member of House republican leadership and George H.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Bush's secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore and Kemp debated once, in one of the lowest rated debates in history.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore held his own against Kemp, and kept President Clinton's large lead against Dole stable.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On November 5, 1996, Clinton and Gore were re-elected as president and vice-president with 379 electoral votes and an 8% margin of victory in the popular vote.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Soon afterward, Gore also had to contend with the Clinton–Lewinsky scandal, which involved an affair between President Clinton and a White House intern, Monica Lewinsky.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore initially defended Clinton, whom he believed to be innocent, stating: "He is the president of the country!
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] During a speech that he gave on June 16, 1999, in Carthage, Tennessee, Gore formally announced his candidacy for president.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His major theme was the need to strengthen the American family.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] He was introduced by his eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In making the speech, Gore also distanced himself from Bill Clinton, who he stated had lied to him.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore was "briefly interrupted" by AIDS protesters claiming Gore was working with the pharmaceutical industry to prevent access to generic medicines for poor nations and chanting "Gore's greed kills".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Additional speeches were also interrupted by the protesters.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Texas Governor and likely Republican presidential nominee George W.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Bush was leading Gore 54% to 41% in polls during that time.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore's advisers believed that the "Lewinsky scandal and Bill's past womanizing...alienated independent voters—especially the soccer moms, who stood for traditional values".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Consequently, Gore's presidential campaign "veered too far in differentiating himself from Bill and his record and had difficulty taking advantage of the Clinton administration's legitimate successes".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In one instance "Hillary insisted on being invited [to a Los Angeles fundraiser for the vice president]—over the objections of the event's organizers", where the First Lady "shocked the vice president's supporters by soliciting donations for herself in front of Tipper".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore faced an early challenge by former New Jersey senator Bill Bradley.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Bradley was the only candidate to oppose Gore and was considered a "fresh face" for the White House.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore challenged Bradley to a series of debates which took the form of "town hall" meetings.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore went on the offensive during these debates leading to a drop in the polls for Bradley.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In the Iowa caucus the unions pledged their support to Gore, despite Bradley spending heavily in that state, and Bradley was much embarrassed by his two to one defeat there.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore went on to capture the New Hampshire primary 53-47%, which had been a must-win state for Bradley.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore then swept all of the primaries on Super Tuesday while Bradley finished a distant second in each state.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On March 9, 2000, after failing to win any of the first 20 primaries and caucuses in the election process, Bradley withdrew his campaign and endorsed Gore.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore eventually went on to win every primary and caucus and, in March 2000 even won the first primary election ever held over the Internet, the Arizona Presidential Primary.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] By then, he secured the Democratic nomination.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] As of 2023, Al Gore remains the only presidential candidate in American history who was not the incumbent president to win every single contest in his or her party primary.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On August 13, 2000, Gore announced that he had selected Senator Joe Lieberman of Connecticut as his vice presidential running mate.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Lieberman became "the first person of the Jewish faith to run for the nation's second-highest office".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Many pundits saw Gore's choice of Lieberman as further distancing him from the scandals of the Clinton White House.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore's daughter, Karenna, together with her father's former Harvard roommate Tommy Lee Jones, officially nominated Gore as the Democratic presidential candidate during the 2000 Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles, California.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore accepted his party's nomination and spoke about the major themes of his campaign, stating in particular his plan to extend Medicare to pay for prescription drugs and to work for a sensible universal health-care system.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Soon after the convention, Gore hit the campaign trail with running mate Joe Lieberman.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore and Bush were deadlocked in the polls.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] They participated in three televised debates.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] While both sides claimed victory after each, Gore was critiqued as either too stiff, too reticent, or too aggressive in contrast to Bush.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] There was talk of a potential run in the 2000 presidential race by Gore as early as January 1998.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore discussed the possibility of running during a March 9, 1999, interview with CNN's *Late Edition with Wolf Blitzer*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Former UCLA professor of information studies Philip E.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Agre and journalist Eric Boehlert argued that three articles in *Wired News* led to the creation of the widely spread urban legend that Gore claimed to have "invented the Internet", which followed this interview.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In addition, computer professionals and congressional colleagues argued in his defense.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Internet pioneers Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn stated that "we don't think, as some people have argued, that Gore intended to claim he 'invented' the Internet.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Housing went up, suburban boom happened, everybody became mobile.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Al was attuned to the power of networking much more than any of his elective colleagues.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] His initiatives led directly to the commercialization of the Internet.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In a speech to the American Political Science Association, former Republican Speaker of the House of Representatives Newt Gingrich stated: "In all fairness, it's something Gore had worked on a long time.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] I asked him about the differences he had with Bill Bradley ...
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Gore himself would later poke fun at the controversy.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] In 2000, while on the *Late Show with David Letterman* he read *Letterman's Top 10 List* (which for this show was called, "Top Ten Rejected Gore – Lieberman Campaign Slogans") to the audience.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On election night, news networks first called Florida for Gore, later retracted the projection, and then called Florida for Bush, before finally retracting that projection as well.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Florida's Republican Secretary of State, Katherine Harris, eventually certified Florida's vote count.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] This led to the Florida election recount, a move to further examine the Florida results.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The Florida recount was stopped a few weeks later on December 12 by the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] That ended recounts underway in selected Florida counties, resulting in George W.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] Bush with a 537 vote victory in Florida and consequently Florida's 25 electoral votes, thus the presidency.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] The results of the decision led to Gore winning the popular vote by approximately 500,000 votes nationwide, but receiving 266 electoral votes to Bush's 271 (one District of Columbia elector abstained).
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p01] On December 13, 2000, Gore conceded the election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Bill Clinton and Gore had maintained an informal public distance for eight years, but they reunited for the media in August 2009.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Clinton had arranged for the release of two female journalists who were being held hostage in North Korea.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] The women were employees of Gore's Current TV.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In May 2018, he was included as a member of the Indian Government committee to coordinate year long celebrations of Mahatma Gandhi's 150th birth anniversary from October 2, 2019.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Beginning in 2002, Gore began to publicly criticize the Bush administration.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In a September 23 speech that he gave before the Commonwealth Club of California, Gore criticized Bush and Congress for the rush to war prior to the outbreak of hostilities in Iraq.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He compared this decision to the Persian Gulf War (which Gore had voted for), stating, "Back in 1991, I was one of a handful of Democrats in the United States Senate to vote in favor of the resolution endorsing the Persian Gulf War ...
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] But look at the differences between the resolution that was voted on in 1991 and the one this administration is proposing that the Congress vote on in 2002.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] The circumstances are really completely different ... in 1991, Iraq had crossed an international border, invaded a neighboring sovereign nation and annexed its territory.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In a speech given during the 2004 presidential election, Gore accused George W.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Bush of betraying the country by using the 9/11 attacks as a justification for the invasion of Iraq.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] The next year, Gore gave a speech which covered many topics, including what he called "religious zealots" who claim special knowledge of God's will in American politics.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore stated: "They even claim that those of us who disagree with their point of view are waging war against people of faith." After Hurricane Katrina in 2005, Gore chartered two planes to evacuate 270 people from New Orleans and criticized the Bush administration's response to the hurricane.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 2006, Gore criticized Bush's use of domestic wiretaps without a warrant.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] One month later, in a speech given at the Jeddah Economic Forum, Gore criticized the treatment of Arabs in the U.S. after 9/11 stating, "Unfortunately there have been terrible abuses and it's wrong ...
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore's 2007 book, *The Assault on Reason,* is an analysis of what Gore refers to as the "emptying out of the marketplace of ideas" in civic discourse during the Bush administration.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He attributes this phenomenon to the influence of television and argues that it endangers American democracy.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] By contrast, Gore argues, the Internet can revitalize and ultimately "redeem the integrity of representative democracy".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Referring to his own previous criticism of the Bush administrations, Gore stated: "I waited two years after I left office to make statements that were critical, and then of the policy ...
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] While Gore has criticized Bush for his Katrina response, he has not spoken publicly about his part in the evacuation of 270 patients on September 3 & 4, 2005, from Charity Hospital in New Orleans to Tennessee.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] On September 1, Gore was contacted by Charity Hospital's Neurosurgeon Dr.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] David Kline, who had operated on his son Albert, through Greg Simon of FasterCures.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Kline informed Gore and Simon of the desperate conditions at the hospital and asked Gore and Simon to arrange relief.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] On Gore's personal financial commitment, two airlines each provided a plane with one flight later underwritten by Larry Flax.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] The flights were flown by volunteer airline crews and medically staffed by Gore's cousin, retired Col.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Anderson Spickard and were accompanied by Gore and Albert III.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore used his political influence to expedite landing rights in New Orleans.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] People were speculating that Gore would be a candidate for the 2004 presidential election (a bumper sticker, "Re-elect Gore in 2004!" was popular).
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] On December 16, 2002, however, Gore announced that he would not run in 2004.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] While Gore seriously considered challenging Bush in 2004, the September 11 attacks and the subsequent stratospheric rise in President Bush's popularity as a result of his response to these attacks were strong factors in Gore's December 2002 decision not to run again in 2004.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Despite Gore taking himself out of the race, a handful of his supporters formed a national campaign to draft him into running.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] The draft movement, however, failed to convince Gore to run.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] The prospect of a Gore candidacy arose again between 2006 and early 2008 in light of the upcoming 2008 presidential election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Although Gore frequently stated that he had "no plans to run", he did not reject the possibility of future involvement in politics which led to speculation that he might run.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] This was due in part to his increased popularity after the release of the 2006 documentary, *An Inconvenient Truth*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] During the 79th Academy Awards ceremony, Gore and actor Leonardo DiCaprio shared the stage to speak about the "greening" of the ceremony itself.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore began to give a speech that appeared to be leading up to an announcement that he would run for president.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] However, background music drowned him out and he was escorted offstage, implying that it was a rehearsed gag, which he later acknowledged.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] After *An Inconvenient Truth* won the Academy Award for Best Documentary, speculation increased about a possible presidential run.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore's popularity was indicated in polls which showed that even without running, he was coming in second or third among possible Democratic candidates Hillary Clinton, Barack Obama, and John Edwards.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Grassroots draft campaigns also developed with the hope that they could encourage Gore to run.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore, however, remained firm in his decision and declined to run for the presidency.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Interest in having Gore run for the 2016 presidential election arose in 2014 and again in 2015, although he did not declare any intention to do so.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] After announcing he would not run in the 2004 U.S. presidential election, Gore endorsed Vermont governor Howard Dean in December 2003, weeks before the first primary of the election cycle.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He was criticized for this endorsement by eight Democratic contenders particularly since he did not endorse his former running mate Joe Lieberman (Gore preferred Dean over Lieberman because Lieberman supported the Iraq War and Gore did not).
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Dean's campaign soon became a target of attacks and eventually failed, with Gore's early endorsement being credited as a factor.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In *The New York Times*, Dean stated, "I actually do think the endorsement of Al Gore began the decline", and the *Times* further noted that "Dean instantly amplified his statement to indicate that the endorsement from Mr.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Later in March 2004, Gore endorsed John Kerry and gave Kerry $6 million in funds left over from his own unsuccessful 2000 bid.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore also opened the 2004 Democratic National Convention.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] During the 2008 primaries, Gore remained neutral toward all of the candidates, which led to speculation that he would come out of a brokered 2008 Democratic National Convention as a "compromise candidate" if the party decided it could not nominate one.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore responded by stating that these events would not take place because a candidate would be nominated through the primary process.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Senator Ted Kennedy had urged Gore to endorse Senator Barack Obama, though Gore declined.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] When Obama became the presumptive Democratic nominee for president on June 3, 2008, speculation began that Gore might be tapped for the vice presidency.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] On June 16, 2008, one week after Hillary Clinton had suspended her campaign, Gore endorsed Obama in a speech given in Detroit, Michigan which renewed speculation of an Obama-Gore ticket.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore stated that he was not interested in being vice president again.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] On the timing and nature of Gore's endorsement, some argued that Gore waited because he did not want to repeat his calamitous early endorsement of Howard Dean during the 2004 presidential election.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] On the final night of the 2008 Democratic National Convention, shortly before Obama delivered his acceptance address, Gore gave a speech offering his full support.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Such support led to new speculation after Obama was elected president during the 2008 presidential election that Gore would be named a member of the Obama administration.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] This speculation was enhanced by a meeting held between Obama, Gore, and Joe Biden in Chicago on December 9, 2008.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] However, Democratic officials and Gore's spokeswoman stated that during the meeting the only subject under discussion was the climate crisis, and Gore would not be joining the Obama administration.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] On December 19, 2008, Gore described Obama's environmental administrative choices of Carol Browner, Steven Chu, and Lisa Jackson as "an exceptional team to lead the fight against the climate crisis".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore repeated his neutrality eight years later during the Democratic presidential primaries of 2016 until endorsing Hillary Clinton on July 25, 2016, the first day of that year's Democratic National Convention.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore appeared with her at a rally on Miami Dade College's Kendall Campus on October 11, 2016.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore has been involved with environmental issues since 1976 when as a freshman congressman, he held the "first congressional hearings on the climate change, and co-sponsor[ed] hearings on toxic waste and global warming".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He continued to speak on the topic throughout the 1980s, and is still prevalent in the environmental community.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He was known as one of the *Atari Democrats*, later called the "Democrats' Greens, politicians who see issues like clean air, clean water and global warming as the key to future victories for their party".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 1990, Senator Gore presided over a three-day conference with legislators from over 42 countries which sought to create a *Global Marshall Plan*, "under which industrial nations would help less developed countries grow economically while still protecting the environment".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In the late 1990s, Gore strongly pushed for the passage of the Kyoto Protocol, which called for the reduction in greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He was opposed by the Senate, which passed unanimously (95–0) the Byrd–Hagel Resolution (S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] 98), which stated the sense of the Senate was that the United States should not be a signatory to any protocol that did not include binding targets and timetables for developing as well as industrialized nations or "would result in serious harm to the economy of the United States".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 2004, Gore co-launched Generation Investment Management, a company for which he serves as chair.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] A few years later, Gore would also found the Alliance for Climate Protection, an organization which eventually founded the *We Campaign*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore would also become a partner in the venture capital firm, Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers, heading that firm's climate change solutions group.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He also helped to organize the *Live Earth* benefit concerts.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 2010, he attended WE Day (Vancouver, Canada), a WE Charity event.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He favors replacing the income tax with a carbon tax: "We should tax what we burn, not what we earn.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In a 2014 interview, Gore said: "Over a year ago I changed my diet to a vegan diet, really just to experiment to see what it was like. ...
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore's *An Inconvenient Sequel: Truth to Power*, a sequel to his 2006 film, *An Inconvenient Truth*, premiered at the 2017 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] The film documents his continuing efforts to battle climate change.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] A "Climate and Health Summit" which was originally going to be held by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, was cancelled without warning in late January 2017.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] A few days later, Gore revived the summit, which was held by the Climate Reality Project without the support of the CDC.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 2020, he helped to launch Climate TRACE to independently monitor global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In November 2021, Gore spoke at the early stages of the 2021 United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP26) in Glasgow, Scotland.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He later criticised the Morrison government for failing to increase Australia's 2030 emissions reduction target.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In the late 1980s and 1990s, Gore was criticized for his involvement in asking the EPA for less strict pollution controls for the Pigeon River, which had long been polluted by a paper mill in Canton, North Carolina.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] A number of people and organizations, including Marsha Blackburn, a current U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Senator and former Congresswoman from Tennessee, and a conservative Washington, D.C. think tank, have claimed that Gore has a conflict of interest for advocating for taxpayer subsidies of green-energy technologies in which he has a personal investment.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Additionally, he has been criticized for his above-average energy consumption in using private jets, and in owning multiple, very large homes, one of which was reported in 2007 as using high amounts of electricity.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore's spokesperson responded by stating that the Gores use renewable energy which is more expensive than regular energy and that the Tennessee house in question has been retrofitted to make it more energy efficient.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Data in *An Inconvenient Truth* has been questioned.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In a 2007 court case, a British judge said that while he had "no doubt ...the film was broadly accurate" and its "four main scientific hypotheses ...are supported by a vast quantity of research", he upheld nine of a "long schedule" of alleged errors presented to the court.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He ruled that the film could be shown to schoolchildren in the UK if guidance notes given to teachers were amended to balance out the film's one-sided political views.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore's spokesperson responded in 2007 that the court had upheld the film's fundamental thesis and its use as an educational tool.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 2009, Gore described the British court ruling as being "in my favor".
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] During the COP15 climate change conference in Copenhagen in 2009, Gore cited research from Dr.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Wieslaw Maslowski, a professor of oceanography at the Naval Postgraduate School in California to claim that "Some of the models suggest to Dr.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In a 2009 interview with *The Sunday Times*, Maslowski responded to Gore's claim by saying: "It's unclear to me how this figure was arrived at.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore met Mary Elizabeth "Tipper" Aitcheson at his St.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Tipper followed Gore to Boston to attend college, and they married at the Washington National Cathedral on May 19, 1970.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] They have four children; Karenna Gore (b.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In June 2010, the Gores announced in an e-mail to friends that after "long and careful consideration", they had made a mutual decision to separate.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In May 2012, it was reported that Gore had started dating Elizabeth Keadle of Rancho Santa Fe, California.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Before beginning his political career, he attended the New Salem Missionary Baptist Church in Elmwood, Tennessee.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 1977, when he moved to Arlington County, Virginia, he attended the Mount Vernon Baptist Church.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He and his wife were baptized in 1980 and became members of the church.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 2004, he announced he had left the Southern Baptist Convention, but remained a Baptist.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 2007, he received Ethics Daily's "Baptist of the Year" award for his environmental activism.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He was a keynote speaker at the 2008 New Baptist Covenant convention.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 2008.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] Gore starred in the 2006 documentary *An Inconvenient Truth,* which won an Academy Award for Best Documentary in 2007 and wrote the book *An Inconvenient Truth: The Planetary Emergency of Global Warming and What We Can Do About It*, which won a Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album in 2009.
[src:anti-environmentalism/al-gore-p02] In 2024, Gore was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Joe Biden.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Alain Lipietz was raised in Paris in a middle class, Leftist family.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] His mother was French and his father was a Jewish Pole, who had fled antisemitism in Poland at the age of two and arrived in France in 1924.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Lipietz was a precocious child, winning a prize at the age of 15 for public speaking.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] He studied at the exclusive *École polytechnique* as an engineer (entered in 1966) and the *École Nationale des Ponts et Chaussées* (diploma in 1971).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] He had participated in the May '68 protests in Paris, and seen the plight of miners in the north of France, prompting him to study economics, obtaining a Masters from the Sorbonne in 1972.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] He became a research director at CNRS from 1988 to 2002.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] In 1990 he became chief engineer at the Corps of Bridges and Roads (France), and taught at various Paris universities over the course of his career.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Despite his interests in regional planning and economics, since the beginning of his career he also devoted himself to the analysis of social and environmental issues.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] In particular he contributed to the Regulation school of economic thought, as well as environmental theory and policy.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Francine Compte, a feminist and writer, died of cancer in 2008.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] He married Natalie Gandais in July 2015.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] He was then a candidate of Les Verts for the legislative elections of 1986 in Seine-Saint-Denis, and became the national spokesperson of the French Green Party in 1997.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] He was an elected representative of the Green Party at the European Parliament from 1999 to 2009, serving two terms.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Alain Lipietz was an adviser to the *Commission économique des Verts*, a member of the *Commission française du développement durable* (from 2000) and a member of the *Conseil d'établissement du Collège de France* (since 2001).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] On 21 June 2001, Lipietz was elected as candidate for the French Green Party in the 2002 presidential elections.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] With 50% of the votes cast in the party's primaries, Lipietz narrowly beat rival candidate Noël Mamère.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] However, controversy arose during the summer of 2001, when Lipietz seemed to have appeared sympathetic to separatists jailed for planting bombs in Corsica.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] A second controversy was his opposition to reopening the Mont Blanc Tunnel between France and Italy, which had been closed since the tunnel fire in 1999, which killed 39 people.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Meanwhile, the party dropped from seven to five percent support in opinion polls.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Finally, on 14 October 2001, Les Verts managed to survive a major internal crisis and changed their Presidential candidate, dropping Alain Lipietz to choose Noël Mamère, who had supposedly made the irrevocable decision not to run just a day sooner.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] In 2006 Alain and his sister Hélène, A former Green Senator and lawyer, sued the French government and SNCF, the national railway of France, for reparations for transporting members of their family to the Drancy deportation camp during World War II.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] The case was heard in the French Administrative Court, the body charged with trying cases against the French government and its agencies.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] The defendants argued at trial that they were at the time under orders of the German military; the railroad further argued that the German military threatened to shoot any railroad official who disobeyed their orders.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] The court disagreed, concluding that the Vichy government could not have avoided knowledge of the prisoners' likely deportation to concentration camps, and that SNCF made no effort to either protest the transportation or to transport them in a humane manner.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] The French government accepted the decision, but in 2007 SNCF successfully appealed the decision regarding themselves.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] The appeal court found that SNCF was a separate entity to the government and thus outside the competence of the Administrative court.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] The Lipietz family are understood to be considering a further appeal to the State Council in respect of the claim against SNCF.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Coming fifth, he and colleagues then engineered a coalition with right wing candidates and socialist dissidents, to attain a majority coalition.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] The national Green Party suspended the local EELV Villejuif candidates for this alliance with the right wing, which is against party policy.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Alain Lipietz has become a councillor in the majority coalition and one of the vice-presidents of the Agglomeration of Val de Bièvre.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] Lipietz is a prolific academic author with most of his work spanning regional development and regulation theory, labour economics, and green politics.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alain-lipietz] He has also worked on many of the EC directives regarding the financial sector.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The **Athabasca oil sands**, also known as the **Athabasca tar sands**, are large deposits of oil sands rich in bitumen, a heavy and viscous form of petroleum, in northeastern Alberta, Canada.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] These reserves are one of the largest sources of unconventional oil in the world, making Canada a significant player in the global energy market.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The surge in production is attributed mainly to growth in Alberta's oilsands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The expansion of the Trans Mountain pipeline—the only oil pipeline to the West Coast—will further facilitate this increase, with its capacity set to increase significantly, to 890,000 barrels per day from 300,000 bpd currently.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Despite this growth, there are warnings that it might be short-lived, with production potentially plateauing after 2024.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Canada's anticipated increase in oil output exceeds that of other major producers like the United States, and the country is poised to become a significant driver of global crude oil production growth in 2024.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The exploitation of these resources has stirred debates regarding economic development, energy security, and environmental impacts, particularly emissions from the oilsands, prompting discussions around emissions regulations for the oil and gas sector.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The Athabasca oil sands are named after the Athabasca River which cuts through the heart of the deposit, and traces of the heavy oil are readily observed on the river banks.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Historically, the bitumen was used by the indigenous Cree and Dene Aboriginal peoples to waterproof their canoes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The oil deposits are located within the boundaries of Treaty 8, and several First Nations of the area are involved with the sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The Athabasca oil sands first came to the attention of European fur traders in 1719 when Wa-pa-su, a Cree trader, brought a sample of bituminous sands to the Hudson's Bay Company post at York Factory on Hudson Bay where Henry Kelsey was the manager.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 1778, Peter Pond, another fur trader and a founder of the rival North West Company, became the first European to see the Athabasca deposits after exploring the Methye Portage which allowed access to the rich fur resources of the Athabasca River system from the Hudson Bay watershed.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The bitumen is in a fluid state and when mixed with gum, the resinous substance collected from the spruce fir, it serves to gum the Indians' canoes." He was followed in 1799 by mapmaker David Thompson and in 1819 by British Naval officer John Franklin.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] John Richardson did the first serious scientific assessment of the oil sands in 1848 on his way north to search for Franklin's lost expedition.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The first government-sponsored survey of the oil sands was initiated in 1875 by John Macoun, and in 1883, G.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Hoffman of the Geological Survey of Canada tried separating the bitumen from oil sand with the use of water and reported that it separated readily.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Photos of the Athabasca oil sands were also featured in Canadian writer and adventurer, Agnes Deans Cameron's, best-selling book *The New North* which recounted her 10,000 mi (16,000 km) roundtrip to the Arctic Ocean.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Her photographs were reproduced in 2011–2012 in an exhibit at the Canadian Museum of Civilization in Ottawa, and included photos of Count Alfred Von Hammerstein's oil drill works along the Athabasca River.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 1926, Karl Clark of the University of Alberta received a patent for a hot water separation process which was the forerunner of today's thermal extraction processes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Several attempts to implement it had varying degrees of success.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The plan was discussed in the October 1976 *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] A patent was granted for the intended process in 1964.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The nuclear heating option is considered a forerunner to some of the conventional heating methods used to extract tar sands oil.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In April 1959, the Federal Mines Department approved Project Oilsand.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] However, it was subsequently cancelled in 1962.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The oil sands, which are typically 40 to 60 metres (130 to 200 ft) thick and sit on top of relatively flat limestone, are relatively easy to access.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] They lie under 1 to 3 m (3 ft 3 in to 9 ft 10 in) of waterlogged muskeg, 0 to 75 metres (0 to 246 ft) of clay and barren sand.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As a result of the easy accessibility, the world's first oil-sands mine was in the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Commercial production of oil from the Athabasca oil sands began in 1967, with the opening of the Great Canadian Oil Sands (GCOS) plant in Fort McMurray.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] It was the first operational oil sands project in the world, owned and operated by the American parent company, Sun Oil Company.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] When the US$240 million plant officially opened with a capacity of 45,000 barrels per day (7,200 m3/d), it marked the beginning of commercial development of the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 2013 McKenzie-Brown listed industrialist J.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Howard Pew as one of the six visionaries who built the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] By the time of his death in 1971, the Pew family were ranked by *Forbes* magazine as one of the half-dozen wealthiest families in America.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The Great Canadian Oil Sands Limited (then a subsidiary of Sun Oil Company but now incorporated into an independent company known as Suncor Energy Inc.) produced 30,000 barrels per day (4,800 m3/d) of synthetic crude oil.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The true size of the Canadian oil sands deposits became known in the 1970s.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The Syncrude mine is now the largest mine (by area) in the world, with mines potentially covering 140,000 km2 (54,000 sq mi).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Development was inhibited by declining world oil prices, and the second mine, operated by the Syncrude consortium, did not begin operating until 1978, after the 1973 oil crisis sparked investor interest.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] However, the price of oil subsided afterwards and although the 1979 energy crisis caused oil prices to peak again, during the 1980s, oil prices declined to very low levels causing considerable retrenchment in the oil industry.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 1979, Sun formed Suncor by merging its Canadian refining and retailing interests with Great Canadian Oil Sands and its conventional oil and gas interests.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 1981, the Government of Ontario purchased a 25% stake in the company but divested it in 1993.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 1995, Sun Oil also divested its interest in the company, although Suncor maintained the Sunoco retail brand in Canada.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Suncor took advantage of these two divestitures to become an independent, widely held public company.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Suncor continued to grow and continued to produce more and more oil from its oil sands operations regardless of fluctuating market prices, and eventually became bigger than its former parent company.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 2009, Suncor acquired the formerly Canadian government owned oil company, Petro-Canada, which turned Suncor into the largest petroleum company in Canada and one of the biggest Canadian companies.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Suncor Energy is now a Canadian company completely unaffiliated with its former American parent company.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Sun Oil Company became known as Sunoco, but later left the oil production and refining business, and has since become a retail gasoline distributor owned by Energy Transfer Partners of Dallas, Texas.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In Canada, Suncor Energy converted all of its Sunoco stations (which were all in Ontario) to Petro-Canada sites in order to unify all of its downstream retail operations under the Petro-Canada banner and discontinue paying licensing fees for the Sunoco brand.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Nationwide, Petro-Canada's upstream product supplier and parent company is Suncor Energy.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Suncor Energy continues to operate just one Sunoco retail site in Ontario.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] At the turn of the 21st century, oil sands development in Canada started to take off, with an expansion at the Suncor mine, a new mine and expansion at Syncrude, and a new mine by Royal Dutch Shell associated with their new Scotford Upgrader near Edmonton.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Three new large steam-assisted gravity drainage (SAGD) projects were added – Foster Creek, Surmont, and MacKay River – by different companies, all of which have since been bought by larger companies.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Shell Canada's third mine began operating in 2003.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] However, as a result of oil price increases since 2003, the existing mines have been greatly expanded and new ones were built.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Oil sands were by then the source of 62% of Alberta's total oil production and 47% of all oil produced in Canada.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As of 2010, oil sands production had increased to over 1.6 million barrels per day (250,000 m3/d) to exceed conventional oil production in Canada.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] 53% of this was produced by surface mining and 47% by in-situ techniques.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 2012, oil production from oil sands was 1.8 million barrels per day (290,000 m3/d).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The massive development of tight oil extraction in the Bakken and Permian Basin in the United States transformed the oil industry rapidly, reducing importation of foreign oil dramatically.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As with the oil sands, production costs of shale oil are higher than those of conventional oil.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] A combination of factors, among them oversupply and geopolitical rivalries, drove the price of oil down from more than 100 dollars a barrel in 2013 to less than 40 dollars three years later.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Lingering low oil prices prompted companies to cancel new investments in the oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] From May to July 2016, a wildfire spread from Fort McMurray across northern Alberta, burning approximately 590,000 hectares (1,500,000 acres) of forested areas and destroying approximately 2,400 homes and buildings.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] 88,000 people were forced from their homes in what became the largest wildfire evacuation in Alberta's history and the costliest disaster in Canadian history.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The wildfire halted oil sands production at facilities north of Fort McMurray.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Shell Canada shut down output at its Albian Sands mining operation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Suncor Energy and Syncrude Canada also scaled back operations and evacuated employees and their families.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Approximately one million barrels of oil a day, equal to a quarter of Canada's oil production, was halted as a result of the fire in May.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] This continued into June at a rate of 700,000 barrels per day.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The lost output was a contributing factor to rises in global oil prices.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The scaled back operations, along with a refinery outage in Edmonton, caused many gas stations to run out of gas throughout Western Canada.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In 2018, oil sands production reached 3.1 million barrels per day (490,000 m3/d).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Until 2014, industry groups believed oil sands production levels could reach 5 Mbbl/d (790,000 m3/d) by 2030.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As of 2021, after a slowdown in investment, analyst are predicting it could reach 3.8 Mbbl/d (600,000 m3/d) by that time.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Canada is the largest source of oil imported by the United States, supplying 3 million barrels per day (480,000 m3/d) chiefly from oil sands sources as of 2019.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Industry observers went from believing there might be excess pipeline capacity to warning that it was insufficient to accommodate oil sands production growth, after several pipeline projects were abandoned or cancelled.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The North Gateway project to Kitimat, British Columbia, which would have been built by Enbridge, operator of the Enbridge Pipeline System which also serves the area, was cancelled in 2016.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Similarly, after lengthy environmentalist and First Nation group opposition, Keystone XL, a pipeline project from Alberta to Gulf coast refineries, was cancelled in 2021.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Other projects, using existing rights of way, are being built, like Kinder Morgan's Trans Mountain Expansion, nationalized in 2018, or Enbridge's Line 9, reversed to feed refineries in Quebec.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Between January 2019 and December 2020, the Alberta government imposed a quota to adjust production to pipeline export capacity.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] To compensate for pipeline capacity limitations, shipment of oil by rail increased from less than 50 thousand to 400 thousand barrels per day (64,000 m3/d) between 2012 and 2020.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As of December 2008, the Canadian Association of Petroleum Producers revised its 2008–2020 crude oil forecasts to account for project cancellations and cutbacks as a result of the price declines in the second half of 2008.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The revised forecast predicted that Canadian oil sands production would continue to grow, but at a slower rate than previously predicted.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] There would be minimal changes to 2008–2012 production, but by 2020 production could be 300,000 barrels per day (48,000 m3/d) less than its prior predictions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] This would mean that Canadian oil sands production would grow from 1.2 million barrels per day (190,000 m3/d) in 2008 to 3.3 million barrels per day (520,000 m3/d) in 2020, and that total Canadian oil production would grow from 2.7 to 4.1 million barrels per day (430,000 to 650,000 m3/d) in 2020.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Even accounting for project cancellations, this would place Canada among the four or five largest oil-producing countries in the world by 2020.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In early December 2007, London-based BP and Calgary-based Husky Energy announced a 50–50 joint venture to produce and refine bitumen from the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] BP would contribute its Toledo, Ohio refinery to the joint venture, while Husky would contribute its Sunrise oil sands project.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] BP would modify its Toledo refinery to process 170,000 bbl/d (27,000 m3/d) of bitumen directly to refined products.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The joint venture would solve problems for both companies, since Husky was short of refining capacity, and BP had no presence in the oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] It was a change of strategy for BP, since the company historically has downplayed the importance of oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In mid December 2007, ConocoPhillips announced its intention to increase its oil sands production from 60,000 barrels per day (9,500 m3/d) to 1 million barrels per day (160,000 m3/d) over the next 20 years, which would make it the largest private sector oil sands producer in the world.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] ConocoPhillips currently holds the largest position in the Canadian oil sands with over 1 million acres (4,000 km2) under lease.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] If all these plans come to fruition, these five companies will be producing over 3.3 Mbbl/d (520,000 m3/d) of oil from oil sands by 2028.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The governance of the Alberta oil sands is focused on economic development, and has historically been dominated by the interests of two primary actors; government (federal and provincial) and industry.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Canadian federalism forms the functions and roles of each level of government, in that constitutional power is split so that neither is superior to the other.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The *Constitution Act, 1867*, Section 109 ensures the province full ownership of the lands and resources within its borders.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The province acts as the landowner and the federal government oversees jurisdiction over trade, commerce and taxation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] There is a clear overlap, as resource management influences trade, and trade management influences resources.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As of the 1990s, both the federal and provincial government have been aligned, focusing on regulation, technology and the development of new export markets.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The majority of "ground-level" governance is carried out by a number of provincial institutions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Ottawa has avoided direct investment, preferring to improve the investment climate.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] A prime example of this occurred in 1994, when the federal government rolled out tax breaks allowing 100% of oil sands capital investments to be written off as accelerated capital cost allowances.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The provincial government had a much more direct role in development; investing directly in numerous pilot projects, undertaking joint ventures with the industry and consistently making massive investments in research and development.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Some people have claimed that Alberta features one of the lowest royalty rates in the world.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Since Alberta, unlike US states, owns the vast majority of oil under its surface it can exercise more control over it, whereas US states are limited to severance taxes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] This industry-centric royalty system has been criticised for "promoting a runaway pace of development".
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Industry is the core force of oil sands development.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The first major players, Suncor Energy and Syncrude, dominated the market until the 1990s.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Currently there are 64 companies operating several hundred projects.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The majority of production now comes from foreign-owned corporations, and the maintenance of a favourable climate for these corporations grants them strong influence; much stronger than that of non-productive stakeholders, such as citizens and environmental groups.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Governance (policy, administration, regulation) over the oil sands is held almost entirely by the Ministry of Energy (Alberta) and its various departments.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Critics noted a clear and systemic lack of public involvement at all key stages of the governance process.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In answer to this, the province initiated the Oil Sands Consultations Multistakeholder Committee (MSC) in 2006.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The MSC represents four organisations: the Cumulative Environmental Management Association (CEMA), the Wood Buffalo Environmental Association (WBEA), the Canadian Oil Sands Network for Research and Development (CONRAD) and the Athabasca Regional Issues Working Group (RIWG).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The role of the MSC is to consult and make recommendations on management principles.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The recommendations contained in the MSC's first 2007 Final Report were lauded by several ministers and government representatives, but none have yet been effectively passed into law.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] On October 17, 2012, the Alberta government announced it would follow the recommendations of a working group to develop an agency that would monitor the environmental impact of the oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] "The new science-based agency will begin work in the oil sands region and will focus on what is monitored, how it's monitored and where it's monitored.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] This will include integrated and coordinated monitoring of land, air, water and biodiversity," said a press release from Diana McQueen's office, the Minister of Energy and Sustainable Development.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The provincial government moved to develop the agency after widespread public criticism by environmentalists, aboriginal groups and scientists, who claimed the oil sands would have a devastating, long-term effect on the environment if left unchecked.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] On June 17, 2013, the newly formed corporation, Alberta Energy Regulator (AER) was phased in with a mandate to regulate oil, gas and coal development in Alberta including the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The key characteristic of the Athabasca deposit is that it is the only one shallow enough to be suitable for surface mining.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] About 10% of the Athabasca oil sands are covered by less than 75 metres (246 ft) of overburden.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Until 2009, the surface mineable area (SMA) was defined by the ERCB, an agency of the Alberta government, to cover 37 contiguous townships (about 3,400 km2 or 1,300 sq mi) north of Fort McMurray.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In June 2009, the SMA was expanded to 51+1⁄2 townships, or about 4,700 km2 or 1,800 sq mi.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] This expansion pushes the northern limit of the SMA to within 12 miles (19 km) of Wood Buffalo National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The Albian Sands mine (operated by Shell Canada) opened in 2003.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] All three of these mines are associated with bitumen upgraders that convert the unusable bitumen into synthetic crude oil for shipment to refineries in Canada and the United States.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] For Albian, the upgrader is at Scotford, 439 km south.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The bitumen, diluted with a solvent, is transferred there in a 610 mm (24 in) corridor pipeline.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The Energy Resource Conservation Board has approved over 100 mining and in-situ projects despite the negative environmental impacts.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As of 2012, there were nine active open mining projects, more than 50 approved in-situ projects as well as 190 primary recovery projects extracting bitumen that is free flowing.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The ERCB has also approved 20 projects that are testing unproven technology as well as new versions of existing technologies.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Since Great Canadian Oil Sands (now Suncor) started operation of its mine in 1967, bitumen has been extracted on a commercial scale from the Athabasca Oil Sands by surface mining.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In the Athabasca sands there are very large amounts of bitumen covered by little overburden, making surface mining the most efficient method of extracting it.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The overburden consists of water-laden muskeg (peat bog) over top of clay and barren sand.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The oil sands themselves are typically 40 to 60 metres (130 to 200 ft) deep, sitting on top of flat limestone rock.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Originally, the sands were mined with draglines and bucket-wheel excavators and moved to the processing plants by conveyor belts.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] These early mines had a steep learning curve to deal with before their bitumen mining techniques became efficient.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In the intervening years, more effective in-situ production techniques were developed, particularly steam-assisted gravity drainage (SAGD).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In-situ methods became increasingly important because only about 20% of the Athabasca oil sands were shallow enough to recover by surface mining, and the SAGD method in particular was very efficient at recovering large amounts of bitumen at a reasonable cost.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In recent years, companies such as Syncrude and Suncor have switched to much cheaper shovel-and-truck operations using the biggest power shovels (at least 100 short tons; 91 t) and dump trucks (400 short tons; 360 t) in the world.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] This has held production costs to around US$27 per barrel of synthetic crude oil despite rising energy and labour costs.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] After excavation, hot water and caustic soda (sodium hydroxide) is added to the sand, and the resulting slurry is piped to the extraction plant where it is agitated and the oil skimmed from the top.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Provided that the water chemistry is appropriate to allow bitumen to separate from sand and clay, the combination of hot water and agitation releases bitumen from the oil sand, and allows small air bubbles to attach to the bitumen droplets.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The bitumen froth floats to the top of separation vessels, and is further treated to remove residual water and fine solids.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] About two short tons (1.8 t) of oil sands are required to produce one barrel (1⁄8 short ton; 110 kg) of oil.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Originally, roughly 75% of the bitumen was recovered from the sand.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] However, recent enhancements to this method include Tailings Oil Recovery (TOR) units which recover oil from the tailings, Diluent Recovery Units to recover naphtha from the froth, inclined plate settlers (IPS) and disc centrifuges.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] These allow the extraction plants to recover well over 90% of the bitumen in the sand.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] After oil extraction, the spent sand and other materials are then returned to the mine, which is eventually reclaimed.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Alberta Taciuk Process technology extracts bitumen from oil sands through a dry retorting.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] During this process, oil sand is moved through a rotating drum, cracking the bitumen with heat and producing lighter hydrocarbons.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Although tested, this technology is not in commercial use yet.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The original process for extraction of bitumen from the sands was developed by Dr.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Karl Clark, working with the Alberta Research Council in the 1920s.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Today, all of the producers doing surface mining, such as Syncrude Canada, Suncor Energy and Albian Sands Energy etc., use a variation of the Clark Hot Water Extraction (CHWE) process.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In this process, the ores are mined using open-pit mining technology.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The mined ore is then crushed for size reduction.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Hot water at 50–80 °C (122–176 °F) is added to the ore and the formed slurry is transported using hydrotransport line to a primary separation vessel (PSV) where bitumen is recovered by flotation as bitumen froth.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The recovered bitumen froth consists of 60% bitumen, 30% water and 10% solids by weight.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The recovered bitumen froth needs to be cleaned to reject the contained solids and water to meet the requirement of downstream upgrading processes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Depending on the bitumen content in the ore, between 90 and 100% of the bitumen can be recovered using modern hot water extraction techniques.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Steam-assisted gravity drainage (SAGD) is an enhanced oil recovery technology for producing heavy crude oil and bitumen.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] It is an advanced form of steam stimulation in which a pair of horizontal wells are drilled into the oil reservoir, one a few metres above the other.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] High pressure steam is continuously injected into the upper wellbore to heat the oil and reduce its viscosity, causing the heated oil to drain into the lower wellbore, where it is pumped out to a bitumen recovery facility.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Roger Butler, engineer at Imperial Oil from 1955 to 1982, invented steam-assisted gravity drainage (SAGD) in the 1970s.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] More recently, *in situ* methods like steam-assisted gravity drainage (SAGD) and cyclic steam stimulation (CSS) have been developed to extract bitumen from deep deposits by injecting steam to heat the sands and reduce the bitumen viscosity so that it can be pumped out like conventional crude oil.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] The standard extraction process requires huge amounts of natural gas.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As of 2007, the oil sands industry used about 4% of the Western Canada Sedimentary Basin natural gas production.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] By 2015, this may increase two-and-a-half-fold.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] According to the National Energy Board, it requires about 1,200 cubic feet (34 m3) of natural gas to produce one barrel of bitumen from *in situ* projects and about 700 cubic feet (20 m3) for integrated projects.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] Since a barrel of oil equivalent is about 6,000 cubic feet (170 m3) of gas, this represents a large gain in energy.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] That being the case, it is likely that Alberta regulators will reduce exports of natural gas to the United States in order to provide fuel to the oil sands plants.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] As gas reserves are exhausted, however, oil upgraders will probably turn to bitumen gasification to generate their own fuel.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p01] In much the same way as bitumen can be converted into synthetic crude oil, it can also be converted into synthetic natural gas.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The oil sands have been described by first nations peoples, scientists, lawyers, journalists and environmental groups as ecocide.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Approximately 20% of Alberta's oil sands are recoverable through open-pit mining, while 80% require *in situ* extraction technologies (largely because of their depth).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Open pit mining destroys the boreal forest and muskeg, while *in situ* extraction technologies cause less significant damage.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Approximately 0.19% of the Alberta boreal forest has been disturbed by open pit mining.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Alberta government requires companies to restore the land to "equivalent land capability".
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] This means that the ability of the land to support various land uses after reclamation is similar to what existed, but that the individual land uses may not necessarily be identical.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In some particular circumstances the government considers agricultural land to be equivalent to forest land.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Oil sands companies have reclaimed mined land to use as pasture for wood bison instead of restoring it to the original boreal forest and muskeg.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Syncrude asserts they have reclaimed 22% of their disturbed land, a figure disputed by other sources, who assess Syncrude more accurately reclaimed only 0.2% of its disturbed land.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] A Pembina Institute report stated "To produce one cubic metre (m3) [35 cu ft] of synthetic crude oil (SCO) (upgraded bitumen) in a mining operation requires about 2–4.5 m3 [71–159 cu ft] of water (net figures).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Athabasca River runs 1,231 kilometres (765 mi) from the Athabasca Glacier in west-central Alberta to Lake Athabasca in northeastern Alberta.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The average annual flow just downstream of Fort McMurray is 633 cubic metres per second (22,400 cu ft/s) with its highest daily average measuring 1,200 cubic metres per second.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Water licence allocations total about 1% of the Athabasca River average annual flow, though actual withdrawals for all uses, in 2006, amount to about 0.4%.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In addition, the Alberta government sets strict limits on how much water oil sands companies can remove from the Athabasca River.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] According to the Water Management Framework for the Lower Athabasca River, during periods of low river flow water consumption from the Athabasca River is limited to 1.3% of annual average flow.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The province of Alberta is also looking into cooperative withdrawal agreements between oil sands operators.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Since the beginning of the oil sands development, there have been several leaks into the Athabasca River polluting it with oil and tailing pond water.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The close proximity of the tailing ponds to the river drastically increases the likelihood of contamination due to ground water leakages.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In 1997, Suncor admitted that their tailing ponds had been leaking 1,600 cubic metres (57,000 cu ft) of toxic water into the river a day.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] This water contains naphthenic acid, trace metals such as mercury and other pollutants.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Athabasca River is the largest freshwater delta in the world but with Suncor and Syncrude leaking tail ponds the amount of polluted water will exceed 1 billion cubic meters by 2020.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Natural toxicants derived from bitumen in Northern Alberta pose potential ecological and human health risks to people living in the area.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Oil sands development contributes arsenic, cadmium, chromium, lead, mercury, nickel and other metal elements toxic at low concentrations to the tributaries and rivers of the Athabasca.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] As of 2024, oilsands account for 8% of the total of Canadian emissions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Emissions from the oilsands continue to increase, while most other sources are decreasing.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The processing of bitumen into synthetic crude requires energy generated by burning natural gas.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In 2007, the oil sands used around 1 billion cubic feet (28,000,000 m3) of natural gas per day, around 40% of Alberta's total usage.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] He goes on to say that a US government report in 2005 suggested with current technology conventional oil releases 40 kg of carbon dioxide per barrel while non-conventional oil releases 80–115 kg of carbon dioxide.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Alberta energy suggests lower releases of carbon with improving technology, giving a value of 39% drop in emissions per barrel between 1990 and 2008, however only a 29% reduction between 1990 and 2009.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The forecast growth in synthetic oil production in Alberta also threatens Canada's international commitments.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In ratifying the Kyoto Protocol, Canada agreed to reduce, by 2012, its greenhouse gas emissions by 6% with respect to 1990.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In 2002, Canada's total greenhouse gas emissions had increased by 24% since 1990.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Ranked as the world's eighth largest emitter of greenhouse gases, Canada is a relatively large emitter given its population and is missing its Kyoto targets.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] A major Canadian initiative called the Integrated CO2 Network (ICO2N) promotes the development of large scale capture, transport and storage of carbon dioxide (CO2) as a means of helping Canada to help meet climate change objectives while supporting economic growth.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] ICO2N members represent a group of industry participants, many oil sands producers, providing a framework for carbon capture and storage development in Canada.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Two separate fraud lawsuits were filed against "ExxonMobil involving Alberta's oilsands" in October.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] One was in New York and the second was filed in Massachusetts on October 24.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The proposal, which may take several years to gain regulatory approval, includes the construction of a pipeline to transport captured carbon from over twenty oil sands facilities to an underground storage facility near Cold Lake.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The same month, Athabasca Oil Corporation, Canada's 10th largest oil producer, announced that it would build a carbon capture and storage facility at its Leismer oil sands well site near Conklin, Alberta in partnership with Entropy Inc., which is funding the project.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Athabasca Oil said that it aims for a 30% reduction in emissions from the extraction process by 2025.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In Northern Alberta, oil development activities bring an enormous number of people into a fragile ecosystem.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Historically, population figures have been very low for this region.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Water is easily polluted because the water table reaches the surface in most areas of muskeg.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] With the ever-increasing development and extraction of resources, wildlife are recipient to both direct and indirect effects of pollution.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Woodland Caribou are particularly sensitive to human activities, and as such are pushed away from their preferred habitat during the time of year when their caloric needs are greatest and food is the most scarce.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Humans' effect on the Caribou is compounded by road construction and habitat fragmentation that open the area up to deer and wolves.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Wildlife living near the Athabasca River have been greatly impacted due to pollutants entering the water system.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] An unknown number of birds die each year.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Particularly visible and hard hit are migrating birds that stop to rest at tailing ponds.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] There have been numerous reports of large flocks of ducks landing in tailing ponds and perishing soon after.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Data has been recorded since the 1970s on the number of birds found on tailing ponds.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] There has also been a large impact on the fish that live and spawn in the area.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] As toxins accumulate in the river due to the oil sands, bizarre mutations, tumors, and deformed fish species have begun to appear.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] A study commissioned by the region's health authority found that several known toxins and carcinogens were elevated.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Aboriginal communities that live around the river are becoming increasingly worried about how the animals they eat and their drinking water are being affected.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] While there has been no link yet made between the oil sands and health issues, Matt Price of Environmental Defense says the connection makes common sense.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Deformities in fish and high concentrations of toxic substances in animals have also been identified.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Large volumes of tailings are a byproduct of bitumen extraction from the oil sands and managing these tailings is one of the most difficult environmental challenges facing the oil sands industry.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Tailings ponds are engineered dam and dyke systems that contain solvents used in the separation process as well as residual bitumen, salts and soluble organic compounds, fine silts and water.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The concentrations of chemicals may be harmful to fish and oil on the surface harmful to birds.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] These settling basins were meant to be temporary.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] A major hindrance to the monitoring of oil sands produced waters has been the lack of identification of individual compounds present.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] By better understanding the nature of the highly complex mixture of compounds, including naphthenic acids, it may be possible to monitor rivers for leachate and also to remove toxic components.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Such identification of individual acids has for many years proved to be impossible but a breakthrough in 2011 in analysis began to reveal what is in the oil sands tailings ponds.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Ninety percent of the tailings water can be reused for oil extraction.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] By 2009 as tailing ponds continued to proliferate and volumes of fluid tailings increased, the Alberta Energy Resources Conservation Board issued Directive 074 to force oil companies to manage tailings based on new aggressive criteria.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Government of Alberta reported in 2013 that tailings ponds in the Alberta oil sands covered an area of about 77 square kilometres (30 sq mi).
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Tailings Management Framework for Mineable Oil Sands is part of Alberta's Progressive Reclamation Strategy for the oil sands to ensure that tailings are reclaimed as quickly as possible.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Mature tailings dredged from a pond bottom in suspension were mixed with a polymer flocculant and spread over a "beach" with a shallow grade where the tailings would dewater and dry under ambient conditions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The dried MFT can then be reclaimed in place or moved to another location for final reclamation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Suncor hoped this would reduce the time for water reclamation from tailings to weeks rather than years, with the recovered water being recycled into the oil sands plant.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Suncor claimed the mature fines tailings process would reduce the number of tailing ponds and shorten the time to reclaim a tailing pond from 40 years at present to 7–10 years, with land rehabilitation continuously following 7 to 10 years behind the mining operations.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] For the reporting periods from 2010 to 2012, Suncor had a lower-than-expected fines capture performance from this technology.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Syncrude used the older composite tailings (CT) technology to capture fines at its Mildred Lake project.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Syncrude had a lower-than-expected fines capture performance in 2011–2012 but exceeded expectations in 2010–2011.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Shell used atmospheric fines drying (AFD) technology combined "fluid tailings and flocculants and deposits the mixture in a sloped area to allow the water to drain and the deposit to dry" and had a lower-than-expected fines capture performance.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] By 2010 Suncor had transformed their first tailings pond, Pond One, into Wapisiw Lookout, the first reclaimed settling basin in the oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In 2007 the area was a 220-hectare pond of toxic effluent but several years later there was firm land planted with black spruce and trembling aspen.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Wapisiw Lookout represents only one percent of tailings ponds in 2011 but Pond One was the first effluent pond in the oil sands industry in 1967 and was used until 1997.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] By 2011 only 65 square kilometres were cleaned up and about one square kilometre was certified by Alberta as a self-sustaining natural environment.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Wapisiw Lookout has not yet been certified.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Closure operations of Pond One began in 2007.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The jello-like mature fine tails (MFT) were pumped and dredged out of the pond and relocated to another tailings pond for long-term storage and treatment.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The MFT was then replaced with 30 million tonnes clean sand and then topsoil that had been removed from the site in the 1960s.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The 1.2 million cubic meters (42×10^6 cu ft) of topsoil over the surface, to a depth of 50 cm (1 ft 8 in), was placed on top of the sand in the form of hummocks and swales.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] It was then planted with reclamation plants.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In March 2012 an alliance of oil companies called Canada's Oil Sands Innovation Alliance (COSIA) was launched with a mandate to share research and technology to decrease the negative environmental impact of oil sands production focusing on tailings ponds, greenhouse gases, water and land.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Almost all the water used to produce crude oil using steam methods of production ends up in tailings ponds.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Recent enhancements to this method include Tailings Oil Recovery (TOR) units which recover oil from the tailings, Diluent Recovery Units to recover naphtha from the froth, Inclined Plate Settlers (IPS) and disc centrifuges.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In January 2013, scientists from Queen's University published a report analyzing lake sediments in the Athabasca region over the past fifty years.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] They found that levels of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) had increased as much as 23-fold since bitumen extraction began in the 1960s.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Levels of carcinogenic, mutagenic, and teratogenic PAHs were substantially higher than guidelines for lake sedimentation set by the Canadian Council of Ministers of the Environment in 1999.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The team discovered that the contamination spread farther than previously thought.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Pembina Institute suggested that the huge investments by many companies in Canadian oil sands leading to increased production results in excess bitumen with no place to store it.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] It added that by 2022 a month's output of waste-water could result in a 11-foot-deep (3 m) toxic reservoir the size of New York City's Central Park [840.01 acres; 339.94 hectares; 3.3994 square kilometres].
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The oil sands industry may build a series of up to thirty lakes by pumping water into old mine pits when they have finished excavation leaving toxic effluent at their bottoms and letting biological processes restore it to health.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] It is less expensive to fill abandoned open pit mines with water instead of dirt.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Oil sands and especially the related projects, like the construction of a new pipeline, also have a social impact.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Most of all, the local population groups would suffer from the effects of a new oil pipeline.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In addition to the risk of general oil spills, there is now also the danger of gathering food due to the pollution of the fields and waters.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Despite the fact that most people in those areas are not well off, the money is still used to build new projects instead of spending it on improving the quality of life there.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Furthermore, adding a new pipeline to the already existing oil pipelines would increase our dependence on fossil fuels.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In July 2015, one of the largest leaks in Canada's history spilled 5,000 cubic metres of emulsion — about 5 million litres of bitumen, sand and wastewater — from a Nexen Energy pipeline at a Long Lake oil sands facility, south of Fort McMurray.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The subsidiary of China's CNOOC Ltd. automated safety systems had not detected the pipeline fault that caused the spill to cover an area of about 16,000 square metres prior to manual inspection.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Alberta Energy Regulator (AER) revealed the number of pipeline "incidents" in Alberta increased 15% last year, despite the regulator's well-publicized efforts to reduce ruptures and spills.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Athabasca oil sands are in the northeastern portion of the Canadian province of Alberta, near the city of Fort McMurray.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The area is only sparsely populated, and in the late 1950s, it was primarily a wilderness outpost of a few hundred people whose main economic activities included fur trapping and salt mining.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] From a population of 37,222 in 1996, the boomtown of Fort McMurray and the surrounding region (known as the Regional Municipality of Wood Buffalo) grew to 79,810 people as of 2006, including a "shadow population" of 10,442 living in work camps.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The community struggled to provide services and housing for migrant workers, many of them from Eastern Canada, especially Newfoundland.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Fort McMurray ceased to be an incorporated city in 1995 and is now an urban service area within Wood Buffalo.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] By 2015, Venezuela accounted for 18%, Saudi Arabia for 16.1%, and Canada for 10.3% of the world's proven oil reserves, according to NRCAN.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] This was equivalent to about 10% of the estimated 1,700 billion barrels (270×10^9 m3) of bitumen-in-place.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Alberta estimated that the Athabasca deposits alone contain 35 billion barrels (5.6×10^9 m3) of surface mineable bitumen and 98 billion barrels (15.6×10^9 m3) of bitumen recoverable by in-situ methods.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] These estimates of Canada's reserves were doubted when they were first published but are now largely accepted by the international oil industry.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Canada had proved oil reserves of 163 billion barrels as of January 2024, ranking fourth in the world behind Venezuela, Saudi Arabia, and Iran.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Only 3% of the initial established crude bitumen reserves have been produced since commercial production started in 1967.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] At rate of production projected for 2015, about 3 million barrels per day (480×10^3 m3/d), the Athabasca oil sands reserves would last over 170 years.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] However those production levels require an influx of workers into an area that until recently was largely uninhabited.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] By 2007 this need in northern Alberta drove unemployment rates in Alberta and adjacent British Columbia to the lowest levels in history.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] As far away as the Atlantic Provinces, where workers were leaving to work in Alberta, unemployment rates fell to levels not seen for over one hundred years.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Venezuelan Orinoco Oil Sands site may contain more oil sands than Athabasca.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] However, while the Orinoco deposits are less viscous and more easily produced using conventional techniques (the Venezuelan government prefers to call them "extra-heavy oil"), they are too deep to access by surface mining.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Despite the large reserves, the cost of extracting the oil from bituminous sands has historically made production of the oil sands unprofitable—the cost of selling the extracted crude would not cover the direct costs of recovery; labour to mine the sands and fuel to extract the crude.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In mid-2006, the National Energy Board of Canada estimated the operating cost of a new mining operation in the Athabasca oil sands to be CA$9 to CA$12 per barrel, while the cost of an in-situ SAGD operation (using dual horizontal wells) would be CA$10 to CA$14 per barrel.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] This compares to operating costs for conventional oil wells which can range from less than one dollar per barrel in Iraq and Saudi Arabia to over six in the United States and Canada's conventional oil reserves.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The capital cost of the equipment required to mine the sands and haul it to processing is a major consideration in starting production.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The NEB estimates that capital costs raise the total cost of production to CA$18 to CA$20 per barrel for a new mining operation and CA$18 to CA$22 per barrel for a SAGD operation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] This does not include the cost of upgrading the crude bitumen to synthetic crude oil, which makes the final costs CA$36 to CA$40 per barrel for a new mining operation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] However, the development of commercial production is made easier by the fact that exploration costs are very low.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Such costs are a major factor when assessing the economics of drilling in a traditional oil field.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The location of the oil deposits in the oil sands are well known, and an estimate of recovery costs can usually be made easily.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] There is not another region in the world with energy deposits of comparable magnitude where it would be less likely that the installations would be confiscated by a hostile national government, or be endangered by a war or revolution.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] As a result of the oil price increases since 2003, the economics of oil sands have improved dramatically.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] At a world price of US$50 per barrel, the NEB estimated an integrated mining operation would make a rate return of 16 to 23%, while a SAGD operation would return 16 to 27%.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Prices since 2006 have risen, exceeding US$145 in mid-2008 but falling back to less than 40 US$ as a result of the worldwide financial crisis, the oil price recovered slowly and many of the planned projects (expected to exceed CA$100 billion between 2006 and 2015) were stopped or scheduled.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In 2012 and 2013 the oil price was high again, but the US production is increasing due to new technologies, while the gasoline demand is falling, so there is an overproduction of oil.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] But recovering economy can change this in a few years.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] At present the area around Fort McMurray has seen the most effect from the increased activity in the oil sands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Although jobs are plentiful, housing is in short supply and expensive.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] People seeking work often arrive in the area without arranging accommodation, driving up the price of temporary accommodation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The area is isolated, with only a two-lane road, Alberta Highway 63, connecting it to the rest of the province, and there is pressure on the government of Alberta to improve road links as well as hospitals and other infrastructure.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Despite the best efforts of companies to move as much of the construction work as possible out of the Fort McMurray area, and even out of Alberta, the shortage of skilled workers is spreading to the rest of the province.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Even without the oil sands, the Alberta economy would be very strong, but development of the oil sands has resulted in the strongest period of economic growth ever recorded by a Canadian province.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Athabasca oil sands hold geopolitical significance.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] An agreement has been signed between PetroChina and Enbridge to build a 400,000 barrels per day (64,000 m3/d) pipeline from Edmonton, Alberta, to the west coast port of Kitimat, British Columbia.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] If it is built, the pipeline will help export synthetic crude oil from the oil sands to China and elsewhere in the Pacific.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] However, in 2011, First Nations and environmental groups protested the proposed pipeline, stating that its construction and operation would be destructive to the environment.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] First Nations groups also claim that the development of the proposed pipeline is in violation of commitments that the Government of Canada has made through various Treaties and the UN Declaration of the Rights of Indigenous Peoples.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] A smaller pipeline will also be built alongside to import condensate to dilute the bitumen.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Sinopec, the largest refining and chemical company in China, and China National Petroleum Corporation have bought or are planning to buy shares in major oil sands development.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] State Department issued a presidential permit for an Alberta Clipper Pipeline that will run from Hardisty, Alberta, to Superior, Wisconsin.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The pipeline will be capable of carrying up to 450,000 barrels (72,000 m3) of crude oil a day to refineries in the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Indigenous peoples of the area include the Fort McKay First Nation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The oil sands themselves are located within the boundaries of Treaty 8, signed in 1899.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] — The Honourable Clifford Sifton, Superintendent General of Indian Affairs, Report of Commissioners for Treaty No.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Fort McKay First Nation has formed several companies to service the oil sands industry and will be developing a mine on their territory.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Opposition remaining within the First Nation focuses on environmental stewardship, land rights, and health issues, like elevated cancer rates in Fort Chipewyan and deformed fish being found by commercial fishermen in Lake Athabasca.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The Alberta Cancer Board published research of the cancer rates of those living in Fort Chipewyan in 2009.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] While many companies argue that there are not enough chemicals and toxic material in the water due to the development of the oil sands, this report indicates that there is coincidentally a significantly higher rate of cancer within this community.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] There have been many speculations as to why there is a higher rate of cancer in this community; some of those speculations are contamination with the river and the oil sands as well as uranium mining.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The world's largest production of uranium is in this area as well as along the Athabasca River, allowing for easy contamination of the river.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] From 2010 to 2014, the Tar Sands Healing Walk, founded by Indigenous women, was held annually as a demonstration against oil extraction and the damage it caused to local communities and the environment.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] According to some environmental activists, pipeline development poses risks to the cultural, social, and economic way of life of Canada's Indigenous populations.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] For instance, many Indigenous groups rely heavily on local wildlife and vegetation for their survival.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Increased oil production in Canada requires greater oil transport through their traditional lands, which, to some, poses the perception of threats to the survival and traditional way of life of Indigenous groups, as well as the safety and preservation of the surrounding ecosystems.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] First Nations in Alberta have called particular attention to adverse health impacts related to oil sands emissions, asserting that the water quality testing for specific chemicals (heavy metals) has been insufficient.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Aside from environmental concerns, many Indigenous groups have pushed back against pipeline development due to inadequate consultation processes by the federal government.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] As per Section 35 of the Canadian *Constitution Act* Indigenous peoples in Canada are guaranteed the right to be meaningfully consulted with and accommodated when the Crown is contemplating resource development on their lands - see Duty to Consult.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Through a series of Supreme Court of Canada rulings and political protests from Indigenous peoples (see Haida Nation v.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Contrarily, oil sands development also presents many positive impacts and opportunities for Indigenous groups, particularly in Western Canada.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] In fact, over the past two decades, First Nations participation in the energy sector has increased dramatically, from employment and business opportunities to project approval processes and environmental evaluation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Increased Indigenous participation has been encouraged by numerous collaboration agreements with industry, typically in the form of impact benefit agreements (IBAs), which provide not only employment and business ventures, but also job training and community benefits.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Enhanced participation in the energy sector has empowered many Indigenous groups to push for wider involvement by negotiating ownership stakes in proposed pipelines and bitumen storage projects.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] Perhaps the best example of such partnering in Alberta is the agreement between Suncor and Fort McKay and Mikisew Cree First Nations.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The two First Nations acquired a 49% ownership in Suncor's East Tank Farm Development with shares valued at about $500 million making it the largest business investment to date by a First Nation entity in Canada.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] The project has secured support from 35 First Nations along the proposed route; the bands are entitled to at least 35% ownership in exchange for the land use.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] There are currently three large oil sands mining operations in the area run by Syncrude Canada Limited, Suncor Energy and Albian Sands owned by Shell Canada, Chevron, and Marathon Oil Corp.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alberta-oil-sands-p02] For improper diversion of water in 2008–2009, Statoil Canada Ltd. was ordered in 2012 to pay a fine of $5000 and to allocate $185,000 for a training project (The verdict was handed down by the Provincial Court of Alberta, Criminal Division).
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold was influential in the development of modern environmental ethics and in the movement for wilderness conservation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] His ethics of nature and wildlife preservation had a profound impact on the environmental movement, with his ecocentric or holistic ethics regarding land.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He emphasized biodiversity and ecology and was a founder of the science of wildlife management.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo Leopold was born in Burlington, Iowa, on January 11, 1887.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] His father, Carl Leopold, was a businessman who made walnut desks and was first cousin to his wife, Clara Starker.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Charles Starker, who was Carl's father and Clara's uncle, came to the United States from Germany and studied engineering and architecture.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo was named after two of his father's business partners—C.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Rand and Aldo Sommers—although he eventually dropped the use of "Rand".
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Leopold family included younger siblings Mary Luize, Carl Starker, and Frederic.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold's first language was German, although he mastered English at an early age.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's early life was highlighted by the outdoors.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Carl would take his children on excursions into the woods and taught his oldest son woodcraft and hunting.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Aldo showed an aptitude for observation, spending hours counting and cataloging birds near his home.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] His sister Mary later said that even as a young child, "He was very much an outdoorsman, even in his extreme youth.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He was always out climbing around the bluffs, or going down to the river, or going across the river into the woods." He attended Prospect Hill Elementary, where he ranked at the top of his class, and then, the overcrowded Burlington High School.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Every August, the family vacationed in Michigan on the forested Marquette Island in Lake Huron, which the children took to exploring.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1900, Gifford Pinchot, head of the new Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture, donated money to Yale University to begin one of the nation's first forestry schools.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Hearing of this development, teenage Leopold decided he wanted to become a forester.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] His parents agreed to let him attend The Lawrenceville School, a preparatory college in New Jersey, to improve his chances of admission to Yale.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Burlington High School principal wrote in a reference letter to the headmaster at Lawrenceville saying that Leopold was "as earnest a boy as we have in school... painstaking in his work....
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Moral character above reproach." He arrived at his new school in January 1904, shortly before he turned 17.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He was considered an attentive student, although he was again drawn to the outdoors.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Lawrenceville was suitably rural, and Leopold spent much time mapping the area and studying its wildlife.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold studied at the Lawrenceville School for a year, during which time he was accepted to Yale.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Since the Yale School of Forestry granted only graduate degrees, Leopold first enrolled in Sheffield Scientific School's preparatory forestry courses for his undergraduate studies, in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] While Leopold was able to explore the woods and fields of Lawrenceville daily, sometimes to the detriment of his studying, at Yale he had little opportunity to do so; his studies and social life made his outdoor trips few and far between.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold graduated from the Yale Forestry School in 1909.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1909, Leopold was assigned to the Forest Service's District 3 in the Arizona and New Mexico territories.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] At first, he was a forest assistant at the Apache National Forest in the Arizona Territory.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1911, he was transferred to the Carson National Forest in northern New Mexico.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold was stationed in New Mexico until 1924 because he was developing the first comprehensive management plan for the Grand Canyon, writing the Forest Service's first game and fish handbook, and proposing Gila Wilderness Area, the first wilderness area in the Forest Service system.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, Leopold encouraged many changes within New Mexico and Arizona through his time spent in the region developing these plans.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1916, Leopold conducted a speaking tour across New Mexico to encourage the formation of wildlife protection associations among local sportsmen.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The tour began in Silver City, where Leopold met Miles W.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Buford, who went on to establish the Sportsmen's Association of Southwestern New Mexico.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold proposed the creation of a statewide organization, the New Mexico Game Protection Association (NMGPA), which gained support in several cities including Rincon, El Paso, Alamogordo, Cloudcroft, Carlsbad, Roswell, and Albuquerque.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In March 1916, the NMGPA held its first convention, attracting over 1,000 members.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The association adopted three goals: removing game warden appointments from political influence, establishing game refuges within national forests, and implementing a balance of predators.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Following the formation of the NMGPA, Leopold returned to his duties with the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] After the passage of the Term Permit Act, he began siting and surveying locations in Arizona for private recreational development.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] During this time, he also promoted and helped establish Game Protection Associations in Arizona towns such as Flagstaff, Springerville, Tucson, and Payson.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In January 1918, Leopold became Secretary of the Albuquerque Chamber of Commerce.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In this role, he supported various initiatives, including the inclusion of labor organizations in the chamber, the promotion of Hispanic and Pueblo architectural styles, and the drainage of parts of the Rio Grande Valley to expand agricultural land.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold rejoined the Forest Service on August 1, 1919, as Assistant District Forester in Charge of Operations, overseeing Region 3, which included 11 national forests.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] During this period, he became concerned with soil erosion in areas such as the Prescott and Carson National Forests.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In December 1923, he authored *The Watershed Handbook*, a guide for field staff addressing watershed management and recommending the regulation of livestock based on watershed conditions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Just a few months into his new role, Leopold's superior, District Forester Paul Redington, left Region 3 and was succeeded by Frank C.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Pooler—who openly expressed doubts about Leopold's suitability for the position.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Pooler even arranged a new post for Leopold in a different region.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] However, Leopold stood his ground and declined the offer, choosing to stay in Albuquerque and New Mexico, where his family and numerous ongoing projects were deeply rooted.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold's management plan was visionary for its time, emphasizing sustainable use and ecological preservation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He planned to make regulations with tourism, resource protection, recreational planning, and the long-term vision of the park.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He felt that there needed to be a control of commercial enterprises, such as shops and concessions because he described them as "repugnant" to the canyon's natural character.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He suggested there should be designated areas for visitor facilities to minimize environmental disruption.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Additionally, He advocated for the cleanup of garbage and sewage to restore the Colorado River's water quality.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Previously, there was history of people dumping garbage in the river.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He emphasized preserving the canyon's geological and ecological features, including its stratified rock formations and native flora and fauna.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold's plan for recreational planning was to outline strategies for “primitive recreation,” such as hiking, hunting, and fishing, to allow visitors to experience the canyon's wilderness without degrading it.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He recommended trail development to improve access while protecting sensitive areas.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Finally, his long-term vision was to prioritized the “greatest good for the greatest number in the long run,” aligning with U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He laid the groundwork for future park management by advocating for a balance between human enjoyment and ecological health.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Wildlife management was largely unregulated, with game and fish populations often depleted due to overhunting, habitat destruction, and lack of coordinated oversight.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold recognized the need for a systematic approach to manage wildlife resources.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In the handbook, Leopold detailed a section on wildlife population management where he provided a guideline for monitoring and regulating game species, such as deer, elk, and fish, to prevent overharvesting.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He emphasized sustainable hunting and fishing practices to maintain population health.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he wrote a section on habitat conservation which he stressed the importance of preserving habitats, including forests, rivers, and wetlands, to support wildlife.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He included recommendations for mitigating the impacts of grazing and logging on game and fish habitats.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In a section about ecological balance, he introduced early concepts of predator-prey dynamics reflecting on his observations of ecological consequences when predators like wolves were eradicated.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He advocated for a holistic approach to land management considering wildlife as part of the broader ecosystem.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Forest Service rangers to collect data on wildlife populations and enforce regulations.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He proposed coordination with local communities and hunters to promote conservation awareness.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1921, Leopold published an article in the *Journal of Forestry* titled “The Wilderness and Its Place in Forest Recreational Policy,” arguing for the preservation of roadless areas within national forests.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He proposed the Gila as a prime candidate, envisioning it as a space free from roads, motorized vehicles, and industrial development.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He recommended setting aside 750,000 acres of the Gila National Forest headwaters, an area characterized by canyons, mesas, and diverse wildlife, including elk, deer, and trout.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold's proposal gained traction, and in 1924, the Forest Service approved the designation of 755,000 acres as the Gila Wilderness Area, the first such area in the world.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold saw the Gila as a living laboratory for ecological health, where natural processes like predator-prey dynamics could unfold without human interference.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This reflected his early understanding of trophic cascades, later detailed in his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain.” He also valued the Gila for its cultural significance, offering a space for Americans to reconnect with the frontier experience through self-reliant recreation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] On April 5, 1923, he was elected an associate member (now called "professional member") of the Boone and Crockett Club, a wildlife conservation organization founded by Theodore Roosevelt and George Bird Grinnell.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1924, he accepted transfer to the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Forest Products Laboratory in Madison, Wisconsin, and became an associate director.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1933, he was appointed Professor of Game Management in the Agricultural Economics Department at the University of Wisconsin, the first such professorship of wildlife management.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] At the same time he was named Research Director of the University of Wisconsin–Madison Arboretum.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold and other members of the first Arboretum Committee initiated a research agenda around re-establishing "original Wisconsin" landscape and plant communities, particularly those that predated European settlement, such as tallgrass prairie and oak savanna.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Under the Oberlaender Trust of the Carl Schurz Memorial Foundation, Leopold was part of the 1935 group of six U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Forest Service associates who toured the forests of Germany and Austria.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold was invited specifically to study game management, and this was his first and only time abroad.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] His European observations would have a significant impact on his ecological thinking, leading him to view the German policies in favor of blocks of monoculture trees in straight lines as a cautionary tale leading to soil degradation and an overall loss of biodiversity.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] After 1935, Leopold was no longer working for the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Forest Service; he had left the agency in 1928 to work independently and later became a professor at the University of Wisconsin.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold married Estella Bergere, the daughter of a well known ranching family in New Mexico, in northern New Mexico in 1912 and they had five children together.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] They lived in a modest two-story home close to the UW–Madison campus.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] His children followed in his footsteps as teachers and naturalists: Aldo Starker Leopold (1913–1983) was a wildlife biologist and professor at UC Berkeley; Luna B.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold purchased 80 acres in the sand country of central Wisconsin.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The once-forested region had been logged, swept by repeated fires, overgrazed by dairy cows, and left barren.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He put his theories to work in the field and eventually set to work writing his best-selling *A Sand County Almanac* (1949) which was finished just prior to his death.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold died from a heart attack on April 21, 1948, while helping his neighbors control a grass fire by his farm in Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold's home is an official landmark of the city of Madison.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Early on, Leopold was assigned to hunt and kill bears, wolves, and mountain lions in New Mexico.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Local ranchers hated these predators because of livestock losses, but Leopold came to respect the animals.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] One day after fatally shooting a wolf, Leopold reached the animal and was transfixed by a "fierce green fire dying in her eyes." That experience changed him and put him on the path toward an ecocentric outlook.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He developed an ecological ethic that replaced the earlier wilderness ethic that stressed the need for human dominance.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] His rethinking the importance of predators in the balance of nature has resulted in the return of bears and mountain lions to New Mexico wilderness areas.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] By the early 1920s, Leopold had concluded that a particular kind of preservation should be embraced in the national forests of the American West.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He was prompted to this by the rampant building of roads to accommodate the "proliferation of the automobile" and the related increasingly heavy recreational demands placed on public lands.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He was the first to employ the term "wilderness" to describe such preservation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Over the next two decades, he added ethical and scientific rationales to his defense of the wilderness concept.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that it is easier to maintain wilderness than to create it.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold thus rejected the utilitarianism of conservationists such as Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] By the 1930s, Leopold had become one of the first Americans to publish extensively on the startup discipline of wildlife management.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He advocated the scientific management of wildlife habitats by both public and private landholders rather than a reliance on game refuges, hunting laws, and other methods intended to protect specific species of desired game.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The concept of "wilderness" also took on a new meaning; Leopold no longer saw it as a hunting or recreational ground, but as an arena for a healthy biotic community, including wolves and mountain lions.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1935, he helped found the Wilderness Society, dedicated to expanding and protecting the nation's wilderness areas.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He regarded the society as "one of the focal points of a new attitude—an intelligent humility toward Man's place in nature." Science writer Connie Barlow says Leopold wrote eloquently from a perspective that today would be called Religious Naturalism.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Though often forgotten, thinking about population dynamics and consumption also shaped Leopold's ecological vision in profound ways.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] By studying wildlife population fluctuations, Leopold extended many of the ideas about carrying capacity and environmental degradation that Raymond Pearl and Edward Murray East had articulated, and these ideas, in turn, shaped his path-breaking ideas of ecological interconnection.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Moreover, although later readers associate Leopold with wildlife ecology, his career helps show how Malthusian ideas of human society intertwined and overlapped with ideas of nature.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He was greatly influenced by ecologists who themselves gleaned ideas from Malthusian models of human society, and himself often thought of human events—especially the Great Depression and World War II—in terms of the models of population and consumption that he was developing for animals.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] One of the most influential books for Leopold during that period was *Our Vanishing Wildlife* by William Temple Hornaday.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] As one of the earliest works dedicated entirely to the threats facing wild game populations this book significantly shaped Leopold's views.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The book sharpened his focus on the importance of game protection, a concern that would remain central to his thinking for many years to come.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold's nature writing is notable for its simple directness.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] His portrayals of various natural environments through which he had moved, or had known for many years, displayed impressive intimacy with what exists and happens in nature.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This includes detailed diaries and journals of his Forest Service activity, hunting and field experience, as well as observations and activities at his Sand County farm.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He offered frank criticism of the harm he believed was frequently done to natural systems (such as land) out of a sense of a culture or society's sovereign ownership over the land base – eclipsing any sense of a community of life to which humans belong.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The book was published in 1949, shortly after Leopold's death.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] It was structured in a series of monthly essays where he went in depth about land ethics and nature.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Several of these monthly essays were accompanied with sketches from the different landscapes and plants he found.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he would have philosophical segments that would contribute to his land ethic concepts.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Thinking Like a Mountain was originally written during World War II and shows that Leopold's thinking was shaped by that global cataclysm.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In "The Land Ethic", a chapter in *A Sand County Almanac*, Leopold delves into conservation in "The Ecological Conscience" section.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." He noted that conservation guidelines at the time boiled down to: "obey the law, vote right, join some organizations, and practice what conservation is profitable on your own land; the government will do the rest." (p.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's contributions to conservation, particularly his role in establishing the Gila Wilderness Area, are deeply intertwined with the evolution of his philosophical views.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In the early 20th century, Leopold's work with the U.S.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Forest Service in the American Southwest was grounded in the agency's utilitarian ethos, which prioritized resource extraction and economic productivity.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] As a forester in Arizona and New Mexico, Leopold initially approached wildlife management with a focus on maximizing game species for human benefit, a perspective aligned with the Progressive Era's emphasis on efficient resource use.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold's philosophy began to evolve in the 1910s and 1920s, driven by field observations, ecological consequences of his early practices, and intellectual growth.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] A pivotal moment in Leopold's transformation occurred around 1909–1910, during his early years in the Apache National Forest.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain”, Leopold recounts shooting a wolf and watching it die, observing “a fierce green fire” in its eyes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This visceral experience, coupled with witnessing the subsequent ecological fallout, profoundly altered his perspective.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The incident highlighted the role of predators in maintaining ecological balance.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Without wolves, deer populations surged, overgrazing vegetation and triggering a cascade of environmental damage, including soil erosion and loss of biodiversity.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold realized that “the mountain” required all its components—predators, prey, and plants—to function healthily.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This moment marked a shift from viewing wildlife in isolation to understanding ecosystems as dynamic, interdependent systems.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] It planted the seed for his later ecocentric philosophy, where no single species, including humans, could be prioritized at the expense of the whole.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In "Marshland Elegy", an excerpt from *A Sand County Almanac,* Leopold describes the process of destruction for American marshland as well as the efforts to reinvigorate those marshlands after that destruction.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold speak both to the way in which the halting of farmland development in these areas represents positive change for the cranes and other wildlife that relies on marshes as well as the limitations of the strategies implemented by conservationists in the issue.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold criticized conservation strategy in that to make the public cherish the communities we conserve they need to "see and fondle" them which can make the conservation effort self-defeating.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] At the time this essay was written Sandhill Cranes had dwindled to merely 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin, luckily since then the crane population has recovered with the midwest now being home to over 15,000 sandhill cranes.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] These efforts were inspired by this essay and carried out by the Aldo Leopold foundation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] These efforts give a positive example to be looked to for future conservation efforts.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Game Management is deemed Leopold's most important work as it founded a new science by combining the likes of agriculture, biology, ecology, and other sciences.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This book brought about a revolution within conservation and placed Leopold as the founder of the Department of Game Management at The University of Wisconsin.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] For more than 40 years after its publication, it was the leading textbook in the field of wildlife management.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Published nearly 45 years after the death of Leopold, The River of the Mother of God, includes 59 essays drawn from Leopold's unpublished manuscripts found at The University of Wisconsin and Leopold's overlooked published work.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This collection is titled after one of Leopold's most popular essays from 1924, “The River of the Mother of God,” but it spans Leopold's life discussing themes of wilderness preservation, ecology, agriculture, land ethics, and natural esthetics from his teenage years until his last years.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This work dives into a deeper view of Leopold and shows the lasting impact he made on the field of conservation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In *A Sand County Almanac*, Aldo Leopold's essay “A Man’s Leisure Time” provides us with a thoughtful examination of how leisure enriches our lives by deepening our connection with nature.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that how one spends their free time is a good indicator of one's intelligence and character.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold states, “How miserable are the idle hours of the ignorant man!” contributing to his idea that leisure time is meaningful and it is important to take in the nature around when present with the opportunity.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] According to Leopold, leisure activities should not be relaxing time but ways to achieve personal growth and understanding.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He describes hobbies as "a defiance of the contemporary," suggesting that they allow individuals to step away from the relentless pace of modern life and engage in activities that are rewarding and enriching.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold highlights that such pursuits, whether it's collecting fossils or cultivating a garden, can lead to a profound appreciation of the land and how important and amazing nature is.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In this chapter, Mr.Leopold encourages the reader to consider what they do with their free or leisure time in their life.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold advocates for activities that promote a deeper understanding of the natural world.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1933, Aldo Leopold became Professor of Game Management at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, the first position of its kind in the country.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Through his contributions to and knowledge of the field, he developed curricula and ran the program, which was eventually redubbed Wildlife Ecology.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] "Game Management" during this time meant the scientific study and the practical application of techniques for maintaining a healthy wildlife population, especially those that are hunted for sport.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Through his expertise, the area of wildlife management grew from just managing populations within life to a larger egocialcal approach to managing wildlife population.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Game management was a branch of conservation biology to Aldo Leopold.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He was concerned about the whole ecological balance of the environment and not just one species.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He created a field that was hit every area ecology, policy, forestry, and ethics.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He even published a textbook for his class titles "Game management", also published in 1933.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1950 The Wildlife Society honored Leopold by creating an annual award in his name.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, the foundation formed a Leopold Conservation Award to recognize farmers, forestland owners, and private land owners for inspirational conservation efforts and leadership within land ethics.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The *Aldo Leopold Foundation* of Baraboo, Wisconsin, was founded in 1982 by Aldo and Estella Leopold's five children as a 501(c)3 not-for-profit conservation organization whose mission is "to foster the land ethic through the legacy of Aldo Leopold".
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Foundation owns and manages the original Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm and 300 surrounding acres, in addition to several other parcels.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Its headquarters is the green-built *Leopold Center* where it conducts educational and land stewardship programs.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The foundation also acts as the executor of Leopold's literary estate, encourages scholarship on Leopold, and serves as a clearinghouse for information regarding Leopold, his work, and his ideas.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] It provides interpretive resources and tours for thousands of visitors annually, distributes a curriculum about how to use Leopold's writing and ideas in environmental education.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The center maintains a robust website and numerous print resources.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 2012, in collaboration with the United States Forest Service, the foundation and the Center for Humans and Nature released the first full-length film about Leopold, titled *Green Fire: Aldo Leopold and a Land Ethic for Our Time*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The film aired on public television stations across the nation and won a Midwest regional Emmy award in the documentary category.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Wilderness in New Mexico's Gila National Forest was named after him in 1980.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture was established in 1987 at Iowa State University in Ames.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Since its founding, it has pioneered new forms of sustainable agriculture practices.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Forest Service established the Aldo Leopold Wilderness Research Institute at the University of Montana, Missoula in 1993.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Neighborhood Historic District, which includes Leopold's former home in Albuquerque, New Mexico, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2002.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Legacy Trail System, a system of 42 state trails in Wisconsin, was created by the state in 2007 to honor Leopold's contributions to the conservation and outdoor recreation.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This trail covers more than 1,700 miles across the state of Wisconsin.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Many of the trails pass through forests, scenics natural areas, and state parks.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] There are signs, along the trails, to showcase information about Leopold's life, his conservation work, and natural information about the surrounding area.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture in Iowa, created through the 1987 Iowa Groundwater Protection Act is committed to "new ways to farm profitably while conserving natural resources as well as reducing negative environmental and social impacts".
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] An organization, the Leopold Heritage Group, is "dedicated to promoting the global legacy of Aldo Leopold in his hometown of Burlington, Iowa." This groups preserves and shares Leopold's legacy by providing local events, educational programs, and conservation projects.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The "Leopold Heritage Group", supports efforts to maintain Leopold-relates sites around the area for example, his childhood home and many places that he has explored as a child.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] In 1985, Leopold was inducted along with John Muir, a naturalist and preservationist, as the first inductees to the Wisconsin Conservation Hall of Fame.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Hall of Fame is located in Stevens Point, Wisconsin, it was created to recognize the individuals who have made important contributions to conserving the natural state of resources around the state.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Residence Hall at the University of Wisconsin-Madison was named after him.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Leopold's Preserve in Haymarket, Virginia was established in 2014.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] This preserve is a 380-acre park that is committed to preserving diverse ecosystems, natural scenes, and protecting threatened land from industrial and commercial development.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold is well known for being the founder of wildlife management, he played a key role in establishing ethics in the wildlife world.
[src:anti-environmentalism/aldo-leopold] He was a driving force behind the creation of the Gila National Forest Wilderness, and his legacy lives on today as the Gila National Forest has been standing strong since 1924, when the National Forest was created.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] Van der Bellen was born in Austria to Russian and Estonian parents who were refugees from the recently occupied Estonia, and he became a naturalized citizen of Austria together with his parents in 1958.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] He is a descendant of the former Russian Empire's aristocratic Van der Bellen family of patrilineal Dutch ancestry dating back to the 18th century.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] He was a member of the National Council representing the Green Party there from 1994 to 2012, and served as leader of the party as well as its parliamentary group.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] He ran as a nominally independent candidate supported by the Greens in the 2016 presidential election, and finished second out of six in the first round before winning the second round against Norbert Hofer, a member of the Freedom Party.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] On 1 July, before he was due to be sworn into office, the results of the second round of voting were annulled by the Constitutional Court due to absentee votes being improperly counted too early, requiring the election to be re-held.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] On 4 December 2016, he won the ensuing election, taking approximately 54% of the vote.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] Van der Bellen has described himself as a centrist liberal, and supports green and social liberal policies.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] As discussed in his 2015 book, he is supportive of the European Union and advocates European federalism.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] During the presidential election, he appealed to the political centre and was endorsed by the leaders of both the Social Democratic Party and the conservative People's Party.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] Van der Bellen is the second Green president of a European Union country (after Raimonds Vējonis of Latvia) and the first to be directly elected by popular vote.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] In the 18th century, Van der Bellen's patrilineal ancestors emigrated from the Netherlands to the Russian Empire.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] During the Russian Civil War (1917–1922) part of his family escaped from the Bolsheviks and migrated to the newly independent Estonia.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] Before this, Van der Bellen's grandfather Aleksander von der Bellen served as head of the civilian regional government in Pskov.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] In Estonia, the family changed its name from *von der Bellen* to *Van der Bellen*.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] In 1931, Van der Bellen's father Alexander married his Estonian mother, Alma Sieboldt in Kihelkonna, Saaremaa, Estonia.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] Subsequently, his father obtained Estonian citizenship as well.
[src:anti-environmentalism/alexander-van-der-bellen] In 1940, Estonia was invaded, occupied and annexed by the Soviet Union.
